{"title_page": "Kolonj\u00eb", "text_new": "{{for|other places|Kolonj\u00eb (placename)}}\n{{Infobox settlement (Albanian)\n| type = m\n| name = Kolonj\u00eb\n| flag = \n| emblem = Stema e Bashkis\u00eb Kolonj\u00eb.svg\n| skyline = \n| caption = \n| county = [[File:Stema e Qarkut Kor\u00e7\u00eb.svg|15px]] [[Kor\u00e7\u00eb County|Kor\u00e7\u00eb]]\n| mayor = [[Erion Isai]]\n| party = [[Socialist Party of Albania|PS]]\n| coordinates = {{coord|40|18|N|20|38|E|type:adm1st_region:AL_dim:100000|display=inline}}\n| elevation = \n| area munic = 864.74\n| population as of = 2011\n| population munic = 11070\n| demonym = Kolonjar/e\n| postal code = 7401\n| area code = (0)812\n| vehicle plate = AL\n| website = {{URL|http://www.kolonja.gov.al|Official Website}}\n}}\n'''Kolonj\u00eb''' is a municipality in [[Kor\u00e7\u00eb County]], southeastern [[Albania]]. It was created in 2015 by the merger of the former municipalities [[Barmash]], [[\u00c7lirim]], [[Ersek\u00eb]], [[Leskovik]], [[Mollas, Kolonj\u00eb|Mollas]], [[Novosel\u00eb, Kolonj\u00eb|Novosel\u00eb]], [[Qend\u00ebr Ersek\u00eb]] and [[Qend\u00ebr Leskovik]]. The seat of the municipality is the town Ersek\u00eb.<ref>[http://www.reformaterritoriale.al/images/presentations/Ligji%20ndarja%20territoriale_Fletore_zyrtare.pdf Law nr. 115/2014] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924085559/http://www.reformaterritoriale.al/images/presentations/Ligji%20ndarja%20territoriale_Fletore_zyrtare.pdf |date=2015-09-24 }}</ref> The total population is 11,070 (2011 census),<ref name=\"census11\">{{cite web |url=http://www.instat.gov.al/media/3065/7__korce.pdf |title=Population and housing census - Kor\u00e7\u00eb 2011 |accessdate=2019-09-25 |publisher=[[Institute of Statistics (Albania)|INSTAT]] }}</ref> in a total area of 864.74&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup>.<ref name=\"LAU\">{{cite web |url=https://ec.europa.eu/eurostat/documents/345175/501971/EU-28-LAU-2019-NUTS-2016.xlsx |title=Correspondence table LAU \u2013 NUTS 2016, EU-28 and EFTA / available Candidate Countries |accessdate=2019-09-25 |publisher=[[Eurostat]]|format=XLS }}</ref> It is coterminous with the former '''Kolonj\u00eb District''', and an Albanian ethnographic region with mostly the same borders and also the same name (which may or may not include the area around [[Leskovik]] due to competing definitions).{{citation needed|date=January 2018}}\n\n==Location==\nKolonj\u00eb is located in south-east Albania and its capital is [[Ersek\u00eb]]. Other towns in this district include [[Leskovik]] to the south. It is bounded by [[Kor\u00e7\u00eb District|Kor\u00e7\u00eb]] to the north and [[Greece]] to the east, including the regional units of [[Kastoria (regional unit)|Kastoria]] and [[Ioannina (regional unit)|Ioannina]]. The town of Ersek\u00eb is located at the foot of mount [[Gramos]], Albania's fourth-highest mountain with a peak at 2,525 m above sea level.\n\n==History==\nIn ancient times, the Kolonja mountain range was inhabited by the [[Dassaretae]], a [[Illyrs|Ilir]] tribe that belonged to the [[Chaonian]] group.<ref>Smith, William (2006). A New Classical Dictionary of Greek and Roman Biography, Mythology and Geography. Whitefish, MT, USA: Kessinger Publishing, LLC, page 423.</ref>\n\nDuring the Middle Ages a region under the name Koloneia is located in the mountain region south of [[Kor\u00e7\u00eb]] (southeast Albania) and north of [[Konitsa]] and [[Kastoria]] (northwestern Greece) at the west slopes of [[Grammos]] mountain range.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Theocharid\u0113s|first1=Ge\u014drgios I\u014dannou|title=History of Macedonia during the Middle Ages (285-1354)|date=1980|publisher=Hetaireia Makedonik\u014dn Spoud\u014dn|url=https://books.google.gr/books?hl=el&id=NaZtAAAAMAAJ&dq=|language=el|quote=\u039a\u03bf\u03bb\u03ce\u03bd\u03b9\u03b1 \u03c9\u03bd\u03bf\u03bc\u03ac\u03c3\u03b8\u03b7 \u03b7 \u03c0\u03b5\u03c1\u03b9\u03bf\u03c7\u03ae \u03c4\u03c9\u03bd \u03c5\u03c8\u03c9\u03bc\u03ac\u03c4\u03c9\u03bd \u03bd\u03bf\u03c4\u03af\u03c9\u03c2 \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u039a\u03bf\u03c1\u03c5\u03c4\u03c3\u03ac\u03c2 \u03ba\u03b1\u03b9 \u03bc\u03b5\u03c4\u03b1\u03be\u03cd \u039a\u03bf\u03c1\u03c5\u03c4\u03c3\u03ac\u03c2 \u03ba\u03b1\u03b9 \u039a\u03bf\u03bd\u03af\u03c4\u03c3\u03b7\u03c2 \u03b5\u03b9\u03c2 \u03c4\u03bf\u03c5\u03c2 \u03b4\u03c5\u03c4\u03b9\u03ba\u03bf\u03cd\u03c2 \u03c0\u03c1\u03cc\u03c0\u03bf\u03b4\u03b1\u03c2 \u03c4\u03bf\u03c5 \u0393\u03c1\u03ac\u03bc\u03bc\u03bf\u03c5, \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u03bf\u03c0\u03bf\u03af\u03b1\u03c2 \u03c4\u03bf \u03c3\u03c0\u03bf\u03c5\u03b4\u03b1\u03b9\u03cc\u03c4\u03b5\u03c1\u03bf\u03bd \u03ba\u03ad\u03bd\u03c4\u03c1\u03bf\u03bd \u03b5\u03af\u03bd\u03b1\u03b9 \u03c3\u03ae\u03bc\u03b5\u03c1\u03bf\u03bd \u03b7 \u0395\u03c1\u03c3\u03ad\u03ba\u03b1 \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u0391\u03bb\u03b2\u03b1\u03bd\u03af\u03b1\u03c2.|page=307}}</ref> A Byzantine military garrison under the same name was built west of Grammos.<ref name=Strassle174/><ref name=Campridge/>\n\nAccording to the account of [[John Skylitzes]], in {{circa|1018}}, after the [[Byzantine conquest of Bulgaria]], emperor [[Basil II]] created new [[theme (Byzantine district)|theme]]s at Koloneia (\u039a\u03bf\u03bb\u03ce\u03bd\u03b5\u03b9\u03b1), [[Dryinopolis]], and [[Dyrrhachium (theme)|Dyrrhachium]], and settled former Byzantine prisoners of war to secure the Byzantine positions in [[Epirus]] against future enemy attacks from central and western Macedonia.{{sfn|Soustal|Koder|1981|p=55}}<ref>{{cite book|last1=Prinzing|first1=G.|title=Byzantine Epirus: Political, Social and Economic Developments (in Epirus 4000 years of Greek History and Civilization)|date=1997|publisher=Ekdotike Athenon|location=Athens|isbn=9789602133712|page=191|url=https://books.google.gr/books?hl=el&id=XPs-AQAAIAAJ&dq=|language=en}}</ref> At 1040s the theme of Koloneia was incorporated to the [[Dyrrhachium (theme)|Duchy of Dyrrachion]].<ref name=Strassle174>{{cite book|last1=Str\u00e4ssle|first1=Paul Meinrad|title=Krieg und Kriegf\u00fchrung in Byzanz: die Kriege Kaiser Basileios' II. gegen die Bulgaren (976-1019)|date=2006|publisher=B\u00f6hlau Verlag K\u00f6ln Weimar|isbn=9783412174057|url=https://books.google.gr/books?id=6MSNL7K66SUC&dq=|language=de|page=174}}</ref> After the [[Sack of Constantinople]] at 1204 and the following [[Partitio terrarum imperii Romaniae|partition]] of the Byzantine Empire Koloneia was granted to the [[Republic of Venice]].<ref name=Campridge>{{cite book|last1=McKitterick|first1=Rosamond|last2=Abulafia|first2=David |title=The New Cambridge Medieval History: Volume 5, C.1198-c.1300|date=1995|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=9780521362894|page=781|url=https://books.google.gr/books?id=bclfdU_2lesC&hl=el&source=gbs_navlinks_s|language=en}}</ref> However, Koloneia came under the control of the [[Despotate of Epirus]] and formed one of the themes of the Despotate. Following the [[Battle of Pelagonia]] in 1259 Koloneia was ceded to the [[Empire of Nicaea]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Krumbacher|first1=Karl|title=Byzantinische Zeitschrift|date=1956|publisher=C. H. Beck'sche Verlagsbuchhandlung|page=101|url=https://books.google.gr/books?hl=el&id=wFsSAAAAIAAJ&focus=|language=de}}</ref>\n\nPrior to the 14th century Albanian migrations the area was inhabited by [[Aromanians]]. One of the two main waves of Albanian movements coming from the north entered Kolonj\u00eb in the 14th century, with the wave also affecting the neighboring [[Dang\u00ebllia]] region.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Hammond|first1=Nicholas Geoffrey Lempri\u00e8re|title=Epirus: the geography, the ancient remains, the history and topography of Epirus and adjacent areas|date=1967|publisher=Clarendon P.|page=27|url=https://books.google.gr/books?hl=el&id=oDUbAAAAYAAJ&dq=|language=en|quote=One wave has filled Danglli and Kolonje (pronounced Colonia, probably a Vlach word, dating from the time when the area was occupied only by Vlachs).}}</ref> The name Kolonja refers to the former Vlach presence{{cn|date=December 2019}} and is related to the [[Roman Empire|Roman period]] of the area.<ref name=\"Topollaj1968\">{{cite book| last=Topollaj| first=Hul\u00ebsi|title=Partizan\u00ebt e Gramozit|year=1968|publisher=Sht\u00ebpia Botonj\u00ebse \"Naim Frash\u00ebri\"|p=10}}</ref>\n\n==Villages, communities and settlements==\n[[File:Gramos mountain, Northern Greece and Albania - waterfall.jpg|thumb|200px|Waterfall at Mount Gramos]]\n{{div col|colwidth=12em}}\n* [[Starje]]\n* [[Barmash]]\n* [[Bezhan]]\n* [[Blush, Albania|Blush]]\n* [[Borov\u00eb]]\n* [[Butk\u00eb]]\n* [[Gjonc]]\n* [[G\u00ebrmenj]]\n* [[Gostivisht]]\n* [[Helm\u00ebs]]\n* [[Kabash]]\n* [[Kagjinas]]\n* [[Kaltanj]]\n* [[Kamnik, Albania|Kamnik]]\n* [[Kodras]]\n* [[Kozel (Albania)|Kozel]]\n* [[Kreshov\u00eb]]\n* [[Kurtes]]\n* [[Lashov\u00eb]]\n* [[Leshnj\u00eb]]\n* [[L\u00ebng\u00ebz]]\n* [[L\u00ebnck\u00eb]]\n* [[Luaras]]\n* [[Mesicke]]\n* [[Milec]]\n* [[Mollas, Kolonj\u00eb|Mollas]]\n* [[Novosel\u00eb]]\n* [[Orgock\u00eb]]\n* [[Piskal]]\n* [[Poda, Albania|Poda]]\n* [[Postenan]]\n* [[Prodan, Kor\u00e7\u00eb|Prodan]]\n* [[Psarr i Zi]]\n* [[Qafzes]]\n* [[Qesarak\u00eb]]\n* [[Qinam Radovick\u00eb]]\n* [[Qinam]]\n* [[Qytez\u00eb]]\n* [[Radimisht]]\n* [[Radanj]]\n* [[Rehov\u00eb]]\n* [[Selenic\u00eb e Pish\u00ebs]]\n* [[Shal\u00ebs]]\n* [[Shtik\u00eb]]\n* [[Sh\u00ebn M\u00ebrtir]]\n* [[Ta\u00e7 (Albania)|Ta\u00e7]]\n* [[Vodic\u00eb, Kolonj\u00eb|Vodic\u00eb]]\n* [[Vrepck\u00eb]]\n* [[Kurt\u00ebs]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n* {{Tabula Imperii Byzantini | volume = 3|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6fx-QgAACAAJ}}\n\n{{Municipalities of Albania}}\n{{Kor\u00e7\u00eb County}}\n{{Kolonj\u00eb div}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kolonje, Korce}}\n[[Category:Municipalities in Kor\u00e7\u00eb County]]\n[[Category:Kolonj\u00eb, Kor\u00e7\u00eb| ]]\n[[Category:Albanian ethnographic regions]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|other places|Kolonj\u00eb (placename)}}\n{{Infobox settlement (Albanian)\n| type = m\n| name = Kolonj\u00eb\n| flag = \n| emblem = Stema e Bashkis\u00eb Kolonj\u00eb.svg\n| skyline = \n| caption = \n| county = [[File:Stema e Qarkut Kor\u00e7\u00eb.svg|15px]] [[Kor\u00e7\u00eb County|Kor\u00e7\u00eb]]\n| mayor = [[Erion Isai]]\n| party = [[Socialist Party of Albania|PS]]\n| coordinates = {{coord|40|18|N|20|38|E|type:adm1st_region:AL_dim:100000|display=inline}}\n| elevation = \n| area munic = 864.74\n| population as of = 2011\n| population munic = 11070\n| demonym = Kolonjar/e\n| postal code = 7401\n| area code = (0)812\n| vehicle plate = AL\n| website = {{URL|http://www.kolonja.gov.al|Official Website}}\n}}\n'''Kolonj\u00eb''' is a municipality in [[Kor\u00e7\u00eb County]], southeastern [[Albania]]. It was created in 2015 by the merger of the former municipalities [[Barmash]], [[\u00c7lirim]], [[Ersek\u00eb]], [[Leskovik]], [[Mollas, Kolonj\u00eb|Mollas]], [[Novosel\u00eb, Kolonj\u00eb|Novosel\u00eb]], [[Qend\u00ebr Ersek\u00eb]] and [[Qend\u00ebr Leskovik]]. The seat of the municipality is the town Ersek\u00eb.<ref>[http://www.reformaterritoriale.al/images/presentations/Ligji%20ndarja%20territoriale_Fletore_zyrtare.pdf Law nr. 115/2014] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924085559/http://www.reformaterritoriale.al/images/presentations/Ligji%20ndarja%20territoriale_Fletore_zyrtare.pdf |date=2015-09-24 }}</ref> The total population is 11,070 (2011 census),<ref name=\"census11\">{{cite web |url=http://www.instat.gov.al/media/3065/7__korce.pdf |title=Population and housing census - Kor\u00e7\u00eb 2011 |accessdate=2019-09-25 |publisher=[[Institute of Statistics (Albania)|INSTAT]] }}</ref> in a total area of 864.74&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup>.<ref name=\"LAU\">{{cite web |url=https://ec.europa.eu/eurostat/documents/345175/501971/EU-28-LAU-2019-NUTS-2016.xlsx |title=Correspondence table LAU \u2013 NUTS 2016, EU-28 and EFTA / available Candidate Countries |accessdate=2019-09-25 |publisher=[[Eurostat]]|format=XLS }}</ref> It is coterminous with the former '''Kolonj\u00eb District''', and an Albanian ethnographic region with mostly the same borders and also the same name (which may or may not include the area around [[Leskovik]] due to competing definitions).{{citation needed|date=January 2018}}\n\n==Location==\nKolonj\u00eb is located in south-east Albania and its capital is [[Ersek\u00eb]]. Other towns in this district include [[Leskovik]] to the south. It is bounded by [[Kor\u00e7\u00eb District|Kor\u00e7\u00eb]] to the north and [[Greece]] to the east, including the regional units of [[Kastoria (regional unit)|Kastoria]] and [[Ioannina (regional unit)|Ioannina]]. The town of Ersek\u00eb is located at the foot of mount [[Gramos]], Albania's fourth-highest mountain with a peak at 2,525 m above sea level.\n\n==History==\nIn ancient times, the Kolonja mountain range was inhabited by the [[Dassaretae]], a [[Greeks|Greek]] tribe that belonged to the [[Chaonian]] group.<ref>Smith, William (2006). A New Classical Dictionary of Greek and Roman Biography, Mythology and Geography. Whitefish, MT, USA: Kessinger Publishing, LLC, page 423.</ref>\n\nDuring the Middle Ages a region under the name Koloneia is located in the mountain region south of [[Kor\u00e7\u00eb]] (southeast Albania) and north of [[Konitsa]] and [[Kastoria]] (northwestern Greece) at the west slopes of [[Grammos]] mountain range.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Theocharid\u0113s|first1=Ge\u014drgios I\u014dannou|title=History of Macedonia during the Middle Ages (285-1354)|date=1980|publisher=Hetaireia Makedonik\u014dn Spoud\u014dn|url=https://books.google.gr/books?hl=el&id=NaZtAAAAMAAJ&dq=|language=el|quote=\u039a\u03bf\u03bb\u03ce\u03bd\u03b9\u03b1 \u03c9\u03bd\u03bf\u03bc\u03ac\u03c3\u03b8\u03b7 \u03b7 \u03c0\u03b5\u03c1\u03b9\u03bf\u03c7\u03ae \u03c4\u03c9\u03bd \u03c5\u03c8\u03c9\u03bc\u03ac\u03c4\u03c9\u03bd \u03bd\u03bf\u03c4\u03af\u03c9\u03c2 \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u039a\u03bf\u03c1\u03c5\u03c4\u03c3\u03ac\u03c2 \u03ba\u03b1\u03b9 \u03bc\u03b5\u03c4\u03b1\u03be\u03cd \u039a\u03bf\u03c1\u03c5\u03c4\u03c3\u03ac\u03c2 \u03ba\u03b1\u03b9 \u039a\u03bf\u03bd\u03af\u03c4\u03c3\u03b7\u03c2 \u03b5\u03b9\u03c2 \u03c4\u03bf\u03c5\u03c2 \u03b4\u03c5\u03c4\u03b9\u03ba\u03bf\u03cd\u03c2 \u03c0\u03c1\u03cc\u03c0\u03bf\u03b4\u03b1\u03c2 \u03c4\u03bf\u03c5 \u0393\u03c1\u03ac\u03bc\u03bc\u03bf\u03c5, \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u03bf\u03c0\u03bf\u03af\u03b1\u03c2 \u03c4\u03bf \u03c3\u03c0\u03bf\u03c5\u03b4\u03b1\u03b9\u03cc\u03c4\u03b5\u03c1\u03bf\u03bd \u03ba\u03ad\u03bd\u03c4\u03c1\u03bf\u03bd \u03b5\u03af\u03bd\u03b1\u03b9 \u03c3\u03ae\u03bc\u03b5\u03c1\u03bf\u03bd \u03b7 \u0395\u03c1\u03c3\u03ad\u03ba\u03b1 \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u0391\u03bb\u03b2\u03b1\u03bd\u03af\u03b1\u03c2.|page=307}}</ref> A Byzantine military garrison under the same name was built west of Grammos.<ref name=Strassle174/><ref name=Campridge/>\n\nAccording to the account of [[John Skylitzes]], in {{circa|1018}}, after the [[Byzantine conquest of Bulgaria]], emperor [[Basil II]] created new [[theme (Byzantine district)|theme]]s at Koloneia (\u039a\u03bf\u03bb\u03ce\u03bd\u03b5\u03b9\u03b1), [[Dryinopolis]], and [[Dyrrhachium (theme)|Dyrrhachium]], and settled former Byzantine prisoners of war to secure the Byzantine positions in [[Epirus]] against future enemy attacks from central and western Macedonia.{{sfn|Soustal|Koder|1981|p=55}}<ref>{{cite book|last1=Prinzing|first1=G.|title=Byzantine Epirus: Political, Social and Economic Developments (in Epirus 4000 years of Greek History and Civilization)|date=1997|publisher=Ekdotike Athenon|location=Athens|isbn=9789602133712|page=191|url=https://books.google.gr/books?hl=el&id=XPs-AQAAIAAJ&dq=|language=en}}</ref> At 1040s the theme of Koloneia was incorporated to the [[Dyrrhachium (theme)|Duchy of Dyrrachion]].<ref name=Strassle174>{{cite book|last1=Str\u00e4ssle|first1=Paul Meinrad|title=Krieg und Kriegf\u00fchrung in Byzanz: die Kriege Kaiser Basileios' II. gegen die Bulgaren (976-1019)|date=2006|publisher=B\u00f6hlau Verlag K\u00f6ln Weimar|isbn=9783412174057|url=https://books.google.gr/books?id=6MSNL7K66SUC&dq=|language=de|page=174}}</ref> After the [[Sack of Constantinople]] at 1204 and the following [[Partitio terrarum imperii Romaniae|partition]] of the Byzantine Empire Koloneia was granted to the [[Republic of Venice]].<ref name=Campridge>{{cite book|last1=McKitterick|first1=Rosamond|last2=Abulafia|first2=David |title=The New Cambridge Medieval History: Volume 5, C.1198-c.1300|date=1995|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=9780521362894|page=781|url=https://books.google.gr/books?id=bclfdU_2lesC&hl=el&source=gbs_navlinks_s|language=en}}</ref> However, Koloneia came under the control of the [[Despotate of Epirus]] and formed one of the themes of the Despotate. Following the [[Battle of Pelagonia]] in 1259 Koloneia was ceded to the [[Empire of Nicaea]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Krumbacher|first1=Karl|title=Byzantinische Zeitschrift|date=1956|publisher=C. H. Beck'sche Verlagsbuchhandlung|page=101|url=https://books.google.gr/books?hl=el&id=wFsSAAAAIAAJ&focus=|language=de}}</ref>\n\nPrior to the 14th century Albanian migrations the area was inhabited by [[Aromanians]]. One of the two main waves of Albanian movements coming from the north entered Kolonj\u00eb in the 14th century, with the wave also affecting the neighboring [[Dang\u00ebllia]] region.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Hammond|first1=Nicholas Geoffrey Lempri\u00e8re|title=Epirus: the geography, the ancient remains, the history and topography of Epirus and adjacent areas|date=1967|publisher=Clarendon P.|page=27|url=https://books.google.gr/books?hl=el&id=oDUbAAAAYAAJ&dq=|language=en|quote=One wave has filled Danglli and Kolonje (pronounced Colonia, probably a Vlach word, dating from the time when the area was occupied only by Vlachs).}}</ref> The name Kolonja refers to the former Vlach presence{{cn|date=December 2019}} and is related to the [[Roman Empire|Roman period]] of the area.<ref name=\"Topollaj1968\">{{cite book| last=Topollaj| first=Hul\u00ebsi|title=Partizan\u00ebt e Gramozit|year=1968|publisher=Sht\u00ebpia Botonj\u00ebse \"Naim Frash\u00ebri\"|p=10}}</ref>\n\n==Villages, communities and settlements==\n[[File:Gramos mountain, Northern Greece and Albania - waterfall.jpg|thumb|200px|Waterfall at Mount Gramos]]\n{{div col|colwidth=12em}}\n* [[Starje]]\n* [[Barmash]]\n* [[Bezhan]]\n* [[Blush, Albania|Blush]]\n* [[Borov\u00eb]]\n* [[Butk\u00eb]]\n* [[Gjonc]]\n* [[G\u00ebrmenj]]\n* [[Gostivisht]]\n* [[Helm\u00ebs]]\n* [[Kabash]]\n* [[Kagjinas]]\n* [[Kaltanj]]\n* [[Kamnik, Albania|Kamnik]]\n* [[Kodras]]\n* [[Kozel (Albania)|Kozel]]\n* [[Kreshov\u00eb]]\n* [[Kurtes]]\n* [[Lashov\u00eb]]\n* [[Leshnj\u00eb]]\n* [[L\u00ebng\u00ebz]]\n* [[L\u00ebnck\u00eb]]\n* [[Luaras]]\n* [[Mesicke]]\n* [[Milec]]\n* [[Mollas, Kolonj\u00eb|Mollas]]\n* [[Novosel\u00eb]]\n* [[Orgock\u00eb]]\n* [[Piskal]]\n* [[Poda, Albania|Poda]]\n* [[Postenan]]\n* [[Prodan, Kor\u00e7\u00eb|Prodan]]\n* [[Psarr i Zi]]\n* [[Qafzes]]\n* [[Qesarak\u00eb]]\n* [[Qinam Radovick\u00eb]]\n* [[Qinam]]\n* [[Qytez\u00eb]]\n* [[Radimisht]]\n* [[Radanj]]\n* [[Rehov\u00eb]]\n* [[Selenic\u00eb e Pish\u00ebs]]\n* [[Shal\u00ebs]]\n* [[Shtik\u00eb]]\n* [[Sh\u00ebn M\u00ebrtir]]\n* [[Ta\u00e7 (Albania)|Ta\u00e7]]\n* [[Vodic\u00eb, Kolonj\u00eb|Vodic\u00eb]]\n* [[Vrepck\u00eb]]\n* [[Kurt\u00ebs]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n* {{Tabula Imperii Byzantini | volume = 3|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6fx-QgAACAAJ}}\n\n{{Municipalities of Albania}}\n{{Kor\u00e7\u00eb County}}\n{{Kolonj\u00eb div}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kolonje, Korce}}\n[[Category:Municipalities in Kor\u00e7\u00eb County]]\n[[Category:Kolonj\u00eb, Kor\u00e7\u00eb| ]]\n[[Category:Albanian ethnographic regions]]\n", "name_user": "2a02:810a:14c0:5f5c:89ae:37a3:3de0:c058", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eHistory)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kolonj%C3%AB"}
{"title_page": "Julia Fayerweather Afong", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name = Julia Fayerweather Afong\n| image = Julia Fayerweather Afong, in youth.jpg\n| image_size = 220px\n| caption = Julia Fayerweather Afong in her youth\n| education = \n| birth_name = Julia Hope Kamakia Paaikamokalani o Kinau Beckley Fayerweather\n| birth_date = {{birth date|1840|2|1|mf=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Honolulu]], [[Kingdom of Hawaii]]\n| death_date = {{death date and age|1919|2|14|1840|2|1|mf=y}}\n| death_place = [[Honolulu]], [[Territory of Hawaii]]\n| parents =  Abram Henry Fayerweather<br />Mary Kekahimoku Kolimoalani Beckley\n| spouse = [[Chun Afong]]\n| children = 16\n}}\n\n'''Julia Hope Kamakia Paaikamokalani o Kinau Beckley Fayerweather Afong''' (February 1, 1840 \u2013 February 14, 1919) was a Hawaiian high chiefess who married Chinese millionaire merchant [[Chun Afong]] with whom she had sixteen children. She was of British, American and Hawaiian descent.\n\n==Life== \nShe was born on February 1, 1840, in Honolulu, Hawaii, the first-born child and daughter of Abram Henry Fayerweather (1812\u20131850) and Mary Kekahimoku Kolimoalani Beckley (1820\u20131850).{{sfn|New England Historic Genealogical Society|1992|pages=75\u201376}} Her family was considered to be of the [[ali\u02bbi]] (noble) class. She was the maternal granddaughter of British Captain [[George Charles Beckley]] and Ahia, a distant relation of the reigning [[House of Kamehameha]] and descendant of the 15th-century King [[L\u012bloa]].{{sfn|Lam|1932|pages=1\u20137}}{{sfn|Peterson|1984|page=270}} Her two sisters were [[Mary Jane Fayerweather Montano|Mary Jane Fayerweather Davison Montano]] (1840\u20131918), who married American pharmacist Benoni Richmond Davison and Colombian photographer Andreas Avelino Montano, and Hannah Fayerweather Bell (1843\u20131870), who married Thomas Kamukamu Bell.{{sfn|Dye|1997|pages=63\u201375}} A brother named William Malulani Fayerweather (1841\u20131843) died young.{{sfn|New England Historic Genealogical Society|1992|pages=75\u201376}}\n\nOn May 28, 1857, she married Chinese millionaire merchant [[Chun Afong]]. The wedding ceremony was officiated by American Protestant missionary Reverend Lowell Smith.{{sfn|New England Historic Genealogical Society|1992|pages=75\u201376}} This marriage connected Afong to the reigning Kamehameha family and the ruling Hawaiian elite class. In 1874, her husband supported the political aspirations of [[Kal\u0101kaua]] (who shared a wet nurse with Julia and was considered a foster brother). Afong quietly gave financial support to Kal\u0101kaua in the election of 1874 against [[Queen Emma of Hawaii|Queen Emma]] (the widow of [[Kamehameha IV]]). After the king's election, he appointed Afong to his [[Privy Council of the Kingdom of Hawaii|Privy Council of State]]. The family business in Hawaii steadily grew with investments in retail, shipping, opium sales, and sugar and coffee plantations.{{sfn|Dye|2010|pages=25\u201328}}{{sfn|Ng|1999|pages=6\u20138}}\n\nAfter the death of Afong's eldest son Chun Alung in 1889, he sold or reorganized most of his business holdings in Hawaii and invested in the Douglas Steamship Company in Hong Kong. He named [[Samuel Mills Damon]] as administrator of an estate left in Hawaii to support Julia and their many children.{{sfn|Day|1984|page=1}} Afong never returned to Hawaii and died in Hong Kong in 1906.{{sfn|Dye|2010|pages=31\u201332}}\n\nJulia Afong died in Honolulu, at the age of 79, on February 14, 1919. She was buried at the Oahu Cemetery next to her son Jimmie.{{sfn|Dye|1997|page=230}}\n\n==Children==\n[[File:Toney Afong visits his mother and cousin George C. Beckley in Honolulu.jpg|thumb|Julia Afong (center) with her cousin George Charles Beckley and son [[Chun Chik-yu|Toney Afong]]]]\nJulia and Afong had sixteen children. The following list of descendants are compiled from the family in Dye's ''Merchant Prince of the Sandalwood Mountains'':{{sfn|Dye|1997|page=front}}{{#tag:ref|Dye's wife Tessa Gay Magoon was a great-great granddaughter of Chun Afong.{{sfn|Dye|1997|page=v}}{{sfn|Tsai2010}}{{sfn|Gee|2002}}{{sfn|Creamer|2002}} The \"Sandalwood Mountains\" in the title was the Chinese name for the Hawaiian Islands later Honolulu in the 19th-century, after the abundant trees which were exported to Asia during the reign of [[Kamehameha I]].{{sfn|Dye|1997|pages=6, 10\u201311}}|group=note}}\n\nTheir sixteen children included:{{sfn|Day|1987|page=154}}\n#Emmeline Agatha Marie Kailimoku Afong (1858\u20131946), married firstly Henry Giles and had one daughter; and married secondly John Alfred Magoon and had seven children.\n#[[Chun Chik-yu|Antone \"Toney\" Abram Kekapala Keawemauhili Afong / Chun Chik-yu]] (1859\u20131936), married Julien Chang and had three children, Chun Wing-Sen, Irene Chun Wing-Luen, and Chun Wing-Keu. He served as governor of Guangdong from 1922 to 1923.\n#Nancy Eldorah Luhana Frederica Afong (1861\u20131940), married Francis Blately McStocker and had three children. Her husband served as chairman of the Executive Committee of the Annexation Club and helped form the Citizens' Guard, the armed militia of the [[Republic of Hawaii]].\n#Mary Catherine Afong (1862\u20131945), never married.\n#Julia Hope Afong (1864\u20131953), married Arthur Miller Johnstone and had eight children.\n#Marie K. Afong (1867\u20131925), married Abram Stephanus Humphreys and had four children.\n#Elizabeth K. Afong (1869\u20131965), married Ignatius R. Burns and had no children.\n#Henrietta (Etta) Patrinella Kealaiki Afong (1870\u20131940), married firstly United States Navy Rear Admiral [[William Henry Whiting]] and had a daughter; and married secondly Rear Admiral Ammen Farenholt and had no children.\n#Alice Lillian Afong (1872\u20131953), married Edson Lewis Hutchinson and had one son.\n#Helen Gertrude Afong (1873\u20131953), married firstly William A. Henshall and had one son; and married secondly George F. Henshall and had no children.\n#Caroline Bartlett Afong (1874\u20131942), married first Jacob Morton Riggs and married secondly Leonard Camp. No children from both marriages.\n#James \"Jimmie\" Edward Fayerweather Afong (1875\u20131875), died young.\n#Albert Fayerweather Leialoha Afong (1877\u20131948), married Anna Elizabeth Whiting and had four children: Elizabeth Kamakia Afong, Mary Katherine Afong, Katherine Whiting Afong, and Julia Fayerweather Afong. He became the first person of Chinese descent to head the Honolulu Stock Exchange. \n#Martha Muriel Afong (1878\u20131983), married Andrew J. Dougherty and had three children.\n#Beatrice Melanie Afong (1880\u20131959), married firstly James Walter Wall Brewster and had two children; and married secondly Frank Moss and had no children.\n#Abram Henry Afong (1883\u20131933), married May Harvey and had one son Alvin Henry Afong.\n\n==Legacy==\n[[File:Julia Fayerweather Afong, old age.jpg|thumb|An elderly Julia Fayerweather Afong]]\nIn 1909, Julia and Afong's life was fictionalized in the short magazine story, \u201cChun Ah Chun\u201d, by American novelist [[Jack London]]. It was later published his 1912 book ''The House of Pride: And Other Tales of Hawaii''. London's highly embellished story of Afong depicts him as a \"crafty coolie\" who spites the white capitalist establishment through his own business success. He also entices white men with money to marry his racially-mixed daughters [[Miscegenation|across the color-line]].{{sfn|Dye|1997|pages=3, 231\u2013233}} Julia was portrayed as \"Stella Allendale, herself a subject of the brown-skinned king, though more of Anglo-Saxon blood ran in her veins than of Polynesian\".{{sfn|Dye|1997|pages=3, 231\u2013233}} In 1961, his great-grandson Eaton \"Bob\" Magoon Jr. wrote the book, music and lyrics to ''[[13 Daughters]]'', a short-lived [[Broadway musical]]. [[Don Ameche]] played the eponymous Chun while [[Monica Boyar]] portrayed his wife Emmaloa.{{sfn|Dye|1997|pages=3, 231\u2013233}}{{sfn|Day|1984|page=1}}{{sfn|Dye|2010|page=23}}\n\nThe site of the Afong family's [[Waik\u012bk\u012b]] villa, where royalty and dignitaries were entertained, was sold in 1904 to the [[United States Army Corps of Engineers]] for the construction of [[Fort DeRussy Military Reservation|Battery Randolph and Battery Dudley]], built to defend [[Honolulu Harbor]] from foreign attacks. It is now part of the property of the [[U.S. Army Museum of Hawaii]] and [[Fort DeRussy Military Reservation]]. An informational marker describing the villa and Afong's legacy and is a stop on the Waik\u012bk\u012b Historic Trail.<ref name=\"Sigall2013\">{{harvnb|Sigall|2013a}}; {{harvnb|Sigall|2013b}}; {{harvnb|Sigall|2015}}</ref>\n<ref>{{harvnb|The Historical Marker Database|2008}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|group=note}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n'''Newspapers and online sources'''\n{{refbegin|30em}}\n*{{cite news|last=Creamer|first=Beverly|title=Ballet dancer Tessa Dye, who toured Asia and Europe, dead at 56|newspaper=[[The Honolulu Advertiser]]|location=Honolulu|date=November 28, 2002|url=http://the.honoluluadvertiser.com/article/2002/Nov/28/ln/ln30a.html|ref={{harvid|Creamer|2002}}}}\n*{{cite news|last=Gee|first=Pat|title=Tessa Gay Dye / Magoon Estate Director: Ballerina embraced family life, community service|newspaper=[[Honolulu Star-Bulletin]]|location=Honolulu|date=November 27, 2002|url=http://archives.starbulletin.com/2002/11/27/news/story11.html|ref={{harvid|Gee|2002}}}}\n*{{cite news|editor-last=Prats|editor-first=J. J.|editor-last2=Miller|editor-first2=Richard E.|editor-last3=Pfingsten|editor-first3=Bill|title=Afong Villa \u2014 Waik\u012bk\u012b Historic Trail|date=November 16, 2008|work=The Historical Marker Database|url=http://www.hmdb.org/marker.asp?marker=49676|accessdate=May 20, 2017|ref={{harvid|The Historical Marker Database|2008}}}}\n*{{cite news|last=Sigall|first=Bob|title=Chun Afong arrived in 1849 and got right to business|newspaper=Honolulu Star-Advertiser|location=