{"title_page": "Mark Aizlewood", "text_new": "{{good article}}\n{{EngvarB|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Mark Aizlewood\n| image =\n| fullname = Mark Aizlewood<ref>{{Hugman|131|accessdate=1 November 2017}}</ref>\n| height = {{height|ft=6|in=0}}<ref name = \"Garland\">{{cite book |title=Who's Who of Welsh International Soccer Players |last1=Davies |first1=Gareth |last2=Garland |first2=Ian |year=1991 |publisher=Bridge Books |isbn=1-872424-11-2|page=11}}</ref>\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1959|10|1|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Newport, Wales|Newport]], Wales\n| position = [[Defender (association football)|Defender]]\n| youthyears1 =\n| youthclubs1 =\n| years1 = 1975\u20131978\n| years2 = 1978\u20131982\n| years3 = 1982\u20131987\n| years4 = 1987\u20131989\n| years5 = 1989\u20131990\n| years6 = 1990\u20131993\n| years7 = 1993\u20131995\n| years8 = 1995\u20131996\n| years9 = 1996\u20131997\n| years10 = 1997\u20132000\n| clubs1 = [[Newport County A.F.C.|Newport County]]\n| clubs2 = [[Luton Town F.C.|Luton Town]]\n| clubs3 = [[Charlton Athletic F.C.|Charlton Athletic]]\n| clubs4 = [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]]\n| clubs5 = [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]]\n| clubs6 = [[Bristol City F.C.|Bristol City]]\n| clubs7 = [[Cardiff City F.C.|Cardiff City]]\n| clubs8 = [[Merthyr Tydfil F.C.|Merthyr Tydfil]]\n| clubs9 = [[Aberystwyth Town F.C.|Aberystwyth Town]]\n| clubs10 = [[Cwmbran Town F.C.|Cwmbran Town]]\n| caps1 = 38 \n| caps2 = 98 \n| caps3 = 152 \n| caps4 = 70 \n| caps5 = 39 \n| caps6 = 101 \n| caps7 = 39 \n| caps8 =\n| caps9 = 30 \n| caps10 = 69 \n| goals1 = 3\n| goals2 = 2\n| goals3 = 9\n| goals4 = 3\n| goals5 = 1\n| goals6 = 3\n| goals7 = 3\n| goals8 = \n| goals9 = 1\n| goals10 = 0\n| nationalyears1 = 1979\u20131980\n| nationalteam1 = [[Wales national under-21 football team|Wales U21]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 2\n| nationalgoals1 = 0 \n| nationalyears2 = 1986\u20131994\n| nationalteam2 = [[Wales national football team|Wales]]\n| nationalcaps2 = 39 \n| nationalgoals2 = 0\n| manageryears1= 2012\u20132018\n| managerclubs1= [[Carmarthen Town A.F.C.|Carmarthen Town]]\n}}\n'''Mark Aizlewood''' (born 1 October 1959) is a Welsh former professional [[association football|footballer]] and manager.\n\nHaving started his football career at his hometown club [[Newport County A.F.C.|Newport County]], making his professional debut at the age of 16 in 1976, he went on to make over 500 appearances in the [[Football League]], most notably for [[Charlton Athletic F.C.|Charlton Athletic]], [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]] and [[Bristol City F.C.|Bristol City]], and gained 39 caps for [[Wales national football team|Wales]].<ref name=\"atz\">{{cite web |url=http://www.neilbrown.newcastlefans.com/player/markaizlewood.html |title=Mark Aizlewood |publisher=Post War English & Scottish Football League A\u2013Z Player's Database. Neil Brown |accessdate=3 June 2016}}</ref>\n\nFollowing his retirement, Aizlewood worked as an assistant manager with [[Carmarthen Town A.F.C.|Carmarthen Town]] on two occasions and later worked as assistant manager to [[Ian Rush]] at [[Chester City F.C.|Chester City]]. He also spent two years as the technical director of the [[Welsh Football Trust]], being placed in charge of developing youth football in Wales. In 2012, he returned to [[Welsh Premier League]] side Carmarthen Town as manager and lead the club to consecutive [[Welsh League Cup]] victories in 2013 and 2014. His contract as manager was terminated after he was convicted of serious fraud in February 2018.<ref name=BBC42944273/>\n\n==Early life==\nAizlewood was born in [[Newport, Wales|Newport]] and grew up in the [[Ringland, Newport|Ringland]] area. His father was a steelworker who had moved to Newport from [[Wolverhampton]].<ref name=\"goal\">{{cite news |url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-78819443.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180613234743/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-78819443.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=13 June 2018 |url-access=subscription |title=Footballer Reaches His Goal |newspaper=The Western Mail |author=Rhodri Clark |date=2 October 2001 |accessdate=13 June 2018 |via=[[HighBeam Research]]}}</ref> As a child, he attended Alway Juniors School and then [[Hartridge High School]] in Newport.<ref name=\"Argus\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.southwalesargus.co.uk/news/4738302.My_27_year_booze_battle___Mark_Aizlewood/?ref=rc |title=My 27 year booze battle |work=South Wales Argus |author=Ben Frampton |date=13 November 2009 |accessdate=5 January 2014}}</ref> His older brother [[Steve Aizlewood|Steve]] was also a professional footballer.<ref name=\"Cromwell\">{{cite web |url=http://www.southwalesargus.co.uk/sport/1876782.Don_just_misses_out_in_hero_award/ |title=Don just misses out in hero award |work=South Wales Argus |date=4 December 2007 |accessdate=13 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Playing career==\nAfter playing for local youth club Cromwell,<ref name=\"Cromwell\"/> Aizlewood joined his home-town club [[Newport County A.F.C.|Newport County]] at the age of 14, turning down an offer to join [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]].<ref name=\"oz\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ozwhitelufc.net.au/players_profiles/A/AizlewoodM.php |title=Mark Aizlewood |publisher=Oz White LUFC |accessdate=13 June 2018}}</ref> Earning a wage of five pounds per week to cover expenses, he made his professional debut two years later at the age of just 16, whilst he was still attending school.<ref name=\"CCFC players\">{{Cite book | title = The Who's Who of Cardiff City | first = Dean | last = Hayes| publisher = Breedon Books | year = 2006 | p=11 | location=Derby | isbn= 1-85983-462-0}}</ref> He played for Newport for three years, leaving in 1978 to join [[Luton Town F.C.|Luton Town]] for a fee of \u00a350,000, becoming [[David Pleat]]'s first signing at the club.<ref name=\"Argus\"/> After four seasons at Luton, winning the [[Football League Second Division|Second Division]] title in his final year,<ref name=\"82title\">{{cite web |url=https://www.pressreader.com/uk/the-football-league-paper/20140928/282454232214951 |title=Luton Town 1981\u201382 Division Two Champions |publisher=The Football League Paper |author=Neil Fissler |date=28 September 2014 |accessdate=14 June 2018 |via=Press Reader}}</ref> he moved on to [[Charlton Athletic F.C.|Charlton Athletic]] in 1982, again for a fee of \u00a350,000.<ref name=hattersheroes/> He was later appointed club captain and was named the club's player of the year for both the [[1984\u201385 Football League|1984\u201385]] and [[1985\u201386 Football League|1985\u201386]] seasons.<ref name=\"CCFC players\"/>\n\nIn 1987, Charlton received an offer of \u00a3200,000 from [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]] for Aizlewood. Despite resistance from manager [[Lennie Lawrence]], Aizlewood decided to accept the move as the club were then managed by one of his boyhood idols, [[Billy Bremner]].<ref name=\"Hewore\">{{cite web |url=http://www.sheridan-dictates.com/he-wore-the-white-shirt-mark-aizlewood.php |title=Mark Aizlewood |publisher=He wore the shirt |accessdate=3 June 2016}}</ref> Signed as a replacement for [[Ian Snodin]], who had left the club to join [[Everton F.C.|Everton]], he made his debut in a goalless draw with [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]] on 7 February 1987. He became influential almost immediately, missing just one league match for the rest of the season as Leeds finished in fourth position and went on to reach the play-off final, losing to his former club Charlton.<ref name=\"Hewore\"/> Aizlewood was also appointed club captain. However, [[1987\u201388 Football League|the following season]], Leeds struggled to repeat their good form, following the sales of [[Andy Ritchie (English footballer)|Andy Ritchie]] and [[Ian Baird]], and Bremner was sacked from his position as manager. Aizlewood himself became a target for some fans frustration and during a [[Football League Second Division|Second Division]] clash with [[Walsall F.C.|Walsall]] at the end of the [[1988\u201389 Football League|1988\u201389]] season, he reacted to jeers by Leeds' own fans by displaying a [[V sign]], an offensive gesture in the UK,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bbcamerica.com/anglophenia/2013/01/10-things-americans-dont-realize-are-offensive-to-brits |title=10 Things That Americans Don't Realize are Offensive to Brits |publisher=BBC America |author=Ruth Margolis |accessdate=26 July 2018}}</ref> to the crowd after scoring in the closing stages to make the score 1\u20130.<ref name=\"Hewore\"/> Leeds manager [[Howard Wilkinson]] quickly substituted Aizlewood, who blew kisses to the crowd and removed his captain's armband,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.yorkshireeveningpost.co.uk/sport/leeds-united/latest-whites-news/action-replay-aizlewood-goal-salute-was-no-mark-of-respect-1-2210982 |title=Aizlewood salute no Mark of respect |work=Yorkshire Evening Post |date=1 May 2009 |accessdate=5 January 2014}}</ref> for [[David Batty]]. He reacted furiously toward Wilkinson and refused a seat on the bench, returning straight to the dressing room.<ref name=\"Sheridan\">{{cite web |url=http://www.sheridan-dictates.com/he-wore-the-white-shirt-mark-aizlewood.php |title=Mark Aizlewood |publisher=Sheridan Dictates |accessdate=26 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nHe left the club soon after in a \u00a3125,000 move to [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]],<ref name=\"Rush\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.thefootballnetwork.net/main/s418/st70223.htm |title=Ian Rush's assistant, Mark Aizlewood leaves |publisher=The Football Network |author=Chris Thompson |date=5 April 2005 |accessdate=5 January 2014}}</ref> with Aizlewood keen to remain in Yorkshire where his family was settled, reuniting Aizlewood with his former manager at international level, [[Terry Yorath]]. He spent one season at [[Valley Parade]], making 39 league appearances, before moving on to [[Bristol City F.C.|Bristol City]].<ref name=\"Sheridan\"/> He spent three seasons with Bristol, making over 100 appearances in all competitions and scoring three times.<ref name=\"atz\"/>\n\nIn 1993, he returned to Wales to sign for [[Cardiff City F.C.|Cardiff City]]. In his one full season at [[Ninian Park]], the club narrowly avoided relegation to [[Football League Third Division|Division Three]] but did reach the final of the [[Welsh Cup]], losing 2\u20131 to [[Barry Town United F.C.|Barry Town]]. He was also named man of the match in the club's 1\u20130 FA Cup Fourth Round victory over [[Premier League]] side [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] in January 1994.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.walesonline.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/aizlewood-one-citys-great-fa-2408059 |title=Aizlewood: one of City's great FA Cup triumphs |publisher=WalesOnline |date=4 January 2005 |accessdate=14 June 2018}}</ref> During the following season, Aizlewood decided to leave the club in order to take up a player-coach role at [[Merthyr Tydfil F.C.|Merthyr Tydfil]].<ref name=\"CCFC players\"/> He later finished his career with spells at [[Welsh Premier League]] sides [[Aberystwyth Town F.C.|Aberystwyth Town]] and [[Cwmbran Town F.C.|Cwmbran Town]] before retiring in 2000.<ref name=hattersheroes/>\n\n==International career==\n\nHaving previously captained Wales at youth level,<ref name=\"oz\"/> Aizlewood played twice for the [[Wales national under-21 football team|Wales under-21 side]], making his debut in a 1\u20130 defeat to [[England national under-21 football team|England]] on 6 February 1979 before winning his second cap a year later in September 1980 in a 2\u20130 victory over the [[Netherlands national under-21 football team|Netherlands]].<ref name=\"11v11\">{{cite web |url=https://www.11v11.com/players/mark-aizlewood-33981/ |title=Mark Aizlewood |work=11v11.com |publisher=AFS Enterprises |accessdate=14 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nAizlewood made his debut for the [[Wales national football team|Wales]] senior side on 25 February 1986, during a 2\u20131 victory over [[Saudi Arabia national football team|Saudi Arabia]] in [[Riyadh]].<ref name=\"11v11\"/> His last appearance came on 14 December 1994 as Wales lost 3\u20130 to [[Bulgaria national football team|Bulgaria]] in a [[UEFA Euro 1996|Euro 96]] qualifier at [[Cardiff Arms Park]]. He finished his career having won 39 caps for Wales without scoring.<ref name=\"11v11\"/>\n\n==Management and coaching career==\n\n===FAW Trust===\nIn 2001, Aizlewood was appointed as technical director of the [[Welsh Football Trust]], a governing body of the [[Football Association of Wales]] (FAW), following the resignation of Mike Rigg,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-79495135.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180613234503/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-79495135.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=13 June 2018 |url-access=subscription |title=Aizlewood Is Appointed as New Technical Director |newspaper=The Western Mail |author=Ian Hunt |date=27 October 2001 |accessdate=13 June 2018 |via=HighBeam Research}}</ref> a role which he described as his \"dream job\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-79730617.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090525223808/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-79730617.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=25 May 2009 |url-access=subscription |title=Aizlewood Relishes New Task of Shaking Up Welsh Football from Grass Roots |newspaper=Wales on Sunday |author=Paul Abbandonato |date=4 November 2001 |accessdate=14 June 2018 |via=HighBeam Research}}</ref> However, despite increasing the trust's coaching revenues by 75 per cent during his time in charge, he was sacked in December 2003 following an altercation with a BBC camera crew and presenter.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.walesonline.co.uk/news/wales-news/soccer-pundit-sacked-bbc-after-2475591 |title=Soccer pundit sacked by BBC after row |publisher=WalesOnline |date=25 August 2003 |accessdate=13 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-111267386.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180613234637/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-111267386.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=13 June 2018 |url-access=subscription |title=Aizlewood plans to fight after job axe |newspaper=The Western Mail |author=Paul Abbandonato |date=11 December 2003 |accessdate=13 June 2018 |via=HighBeam Research}}</ref> During filming of an interview BBC investigative programme ''X-Ray'', Aizlewood reportedly attempted to forcibly remove a tape from a camera and chased the crew from the trust's offices in Cardiff. He was also accused of assaulting presenter Jane Harvey by \"grabbing her around the neck and pushing her down a flight of steps\" with Harvey describing him as \"berserk\". He was later convicted of assaulting Harvey and ordered to pay a fine of \u00a31,800 and his conduct was described by the judge as \"entirely inappropriate.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/wales/3827067.stm |title=Ex-footballer guilty of presenter attack |publisher=BBC News |date=21 June 2004 |accessdate=5 January 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Chester City===\nAizlewood had a spell on the coaching staff of [[Carmarthen Town A.F.C.|Carmarthen Town]] during [[2003-04 in English football|2003\u201304]], but left to become assistant manager to [[Ian Rush]] at [[Chester City F.C.|Chester City]] for [[2004-05 in English football|2004\u201305]].<ref name=\"carmarthenhistory\">{{cite news |url=http://www.carmarthentownafc.net/history.htm |title=Hanes Y Clwb / Club History |publisher=Carmarthen Town A.F.C. |accessdate=22 May 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090119192957/http://carmarthentownafc.net/history.htm |archivedate=19 January 2009}}</ref> The club made a strong start to the season, embarking on a ten match unbeaten run,<ref name=\"shot\">{{cite web |url=https://www.chesterchronicle.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/rush-aims-parting-shot-after-5285380 |title=Rush aims parting shot after quitting Chester job |work=Chester Chronicle |date=6 April 2005 |accessdate=27 July 2018}}</ref> and Rush was linked to the vacant Wales job but a difficult period in the second half of the season, winning just 2 out of 10 matches, saw the club fall down the table and pressure grew on Rush and his management team.<ref name=\"shot\"/><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/2389422/Rush-rejects-Wales-job.html |title=Rush rejects Wales job |newspaper=The Telegraph |date=2 November 2004 |accessdate=27 July 2018}}</ref> On 4 April 2005, Aizlewood was sacked by Chester chairman [[Stephen Vaughan, Sr|Stephen Vaughan]] without Rush's knowledge.<ref name=\"Rush\"/> Rush himself resigned two days later in protest of the decision, stating \"Loyalty is vital in football and I am a loyal person. When a valued member of my team is dismissed against my wishes, I have no option but to follow my principles.\" When the pair left the club, Chester were nine points clear of the relegation zone, having been bottom of the table when they arrived.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/c/chester/4415035.stm |title=Rush walks out as Chester manager |publisher=BBC Sport |date=6 April 2005 |accessdate=4 June 2016}}</ref> Rush later described Aizlewood as \"one of the best coaches I have worked with.\"<ref name=\"success\">{{cite web |url=https://www.walesonline.co.uk/news/wales-news/success-gambling-depression-drink-crime-14389597 |title=Success, gambling, depression, drink and crime: the fall of Mark Aizlewood |publisher=WalesOnline |author=Robert Harries |date=9 March 2018 |accessdate=14 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Carmarthen Town===\nAizlewood worked as an [[Sports agent|agent]] briefly after leaving Chester as well as managing his business interests.<ref name=\"hattersheroes\">{{cite book | title=Hatters Heroes | publisher=Roger Wash | first= Roger | last= Wash | year=2008 | isbn=978-0-9560832-0-3}}</ref> Having considered leaving football, he was handed his first job as manager in January 2012 by Jeff Thomas, chairman of Carmarthen Town.<ref name=\"success\"/> Returning to the club to replace Tomi Morgan, having previously worked there as assistant manager to Andrew York and [[Deryn Brace]] in separate spells. The club were joint bottom of the Welsh Premier League on his appointment,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.wpl.cymru/news/WPL82318.ink |title=Aizlewood handed task of saving Carmarthen |publisher=Welsh Premier League |date=7 January 2012 |accessdate=14 June 2018}}</ref> along with [[Newtown A.F.C.|Newtown]], but Aizlewood was able to steer them away from relegation. The following year, Aizlewood lead the club to the [[Welsh League Cup]] final, defeating [[The New Saints F.C.|The New Saints]] on penalties to claim the trophy for only the second time in the club's history. They retained the trophy in the 2013\u201314 season, defeating [[Bala Town F.C.|Bala Town]] in the final.<ref name=\"LCfinals\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesw/walleagcuphist.html |title=Wales - List of League Cup finals |publisher=Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation |author=Jo\u00e3o Nunes |accessdate=4 June 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2014, Aizlewood attempted to register himself as a player for Carmarthen, at the age of 55, following an injury crisis at the club prior to a league fixture against [[Rhyl F.C.|Rhyl]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/29911967 |title=Mark Aizlewood: Carmarthen Town boss could play aged 55 |publisher=BBC Sport |date=5 November 2014 |accessdate=4 June 2016}}</ref> However, the plans were ended following a fire at Rhyl's ground which postponed the fixture.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/29935755 |title=Mark Aizlewood: Carmarthen Town boss comeback scuppered by fire |publisher=BBC Sport |date=6 November 2014 |accessdate=4 June 2016}}</ref> He was sacked by the club in February 2018 following his fraud conviction after six years in charge.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.walesonline.co.uk/news/wales-news/carmarthen-town-sack-manager-mark-14248466 |title=Carmarthen Town sack manager Mark Aizlewood after fraud conviction |publisher=WalesOnline |author=Ian Lewis |date=5 February 2018 |accessdate=14 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n\n===Addiction battle===\nAizlewood speaks [[Welsh language|Welsh]],<ref name=\"welshspeaker\">{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/welsh-speak-up-for-their-ancient-tongue-1311562.html |title=Welsh speak up for their ancient tongue |author=Tony Heath |work=The Independent |date=26 August 1996 |accessdate=22 May 2009}}</ref> having taken up lessons during a long injury spell as a player. After becoming proficient with the language he entered the Welsh Learner of the Year competition at the [[National Eisteddfod of Wales]] in [[Llandeilo]] where he was named as the winner.<ref name=\"goal\"/> He released his Welsh language autobiography in 2009, entitled ''Amddiffyn fy Hun'' (Defending Myself) in which he revealed his 27-year-long battle with alcoholism and gambling and contemplating suicide. All proceeds from the book were donated to former England player [[Tony Adams (footballer)|Tony Adams]] Sporting Chance charity.<ref name=\"Argus\"/> His alcohol problem began as an 18 year old, during his time at Luton Town where he found himself with a large disposable income. Remarking on this period, Aizlewood has stated: \"I was making a very good living [...] sometimes I didn't drink for two or three weeks, but then I'd drink for three of four days in one go.\" At his worst, Aizlewood was able to drink a bottle of brandy and 20 pints of lager in one session and still stand. He also developed a gambling addiction and has admitted to losing up to \u00a330,000 in a single day.<ref name=\"Argus\"/> In his book, Aizlewood confessed to once nearly attempting suicide during a trip to [[Rome]] in 2003 due to the severity of his addictions. He stated that on 14 February, he had stood on a motorway bridge in the Italian capital in the early hours of the morning and considered jumping 50&nbsp;ft to the carriageway below,<ref name=\"Argus\"/> commenting \" I didn't have an ounce of fear as I stood on the small wall and looked down at the cars speeding along the road 50ft below me, because I only had one intention: to jump.\"<ref name=\"success\"/>\n\n===Punditry===\nFollowing his retirement from playing, Aizlewood worked as a [[pundit]] for [[BBC Wales]], covering Welsh football, where he developed a reputation as an outspoken critic. He was particularly critical of [[Swansea City A.F.C.|Swansea City]] and their decision to sign several foreign players whilst playing in the lower leagues.<ref name=\"Hostilevetch\">{{cite web |url=http://www.walesonline.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/aizlewood---no-thoughts-hostile-2410226 |title=Aizlewood - no thoughts of hostile Vetch |publisher=WalesOnline |date=27 January 2005 |accessdate=4 June 2016}}</ref> Swansea forward [[Giovanni Savarese]], along with other players, was branded unreliable by Aizlewood and, following Savarese being dismissed for a deliberate elbow on [[Wrexham A.F.C.|Wrexham]] defender [[Mark McGregor]] during the 2001 [[FAW Premier Cup]] final, Aizlewood was accused of racism after calling Savarese a \"coward\" and stating \"but that's foreigners for you\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Football%3A+'Coward'+Gio+under+attack+by+Aizlewood%3B+Swansea+City+0...-a074503594 |title=\"Coward\" Gio under attack by Aizlewood |work=Daily Mirror |author=Tony Rees |date=15 May 2001 |accessdate=4 June 2016 |via=The Free Library}}</ref> His outspoken views of Swansea and their players made him a target for fans of the club and, in October 2002, Aizlewood was attacked by a group of Swansea fans, after commentating at a game against [[Rochdale A.F.C.|Rochdale]] at [[Vetch Field]], who pushed him into a gate, causing him to suffer grazing to his eye. BBC Wales head of sport, Nigel Walker demanded that the club would assure Aizlewood's safety at future matches following the incident.<ref name=\"Hostilevetch\"/>\n\n==Fraud conviction==\nAfter an investigation by various newspapers, in 2012, Aizlewood was one of three men arrested in connection with allegations of fraud regarding \u00a31.6m of government funds that had been given to Luis Michael Training Ltd based in Newport, a company where Aizlewood was serving as a director.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/law/2012/may/17/sfo-football-skills-fraud-probe |title=SFO make arrests in football apprenticeship investigation |work=The Guardian |date=17 May 2012 |accessdate=5 January 2014}}</ref> The company offered football apprenticeships, promising to provide full-time training in football coaching as well as work experience and a \u00a395 weekly salary, to up to 3,800 students.<ref name=\"jailedbbc\">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-43196467 |title=Mark Aizlewood jailed over football apprenticeship fraud |publisher=BBC News |date=26 February 2018 |accessdate=27 July 2018}}</ref> However, the company focused on targeting young players from youth clubs between 2009 and 2011, fraudulently obtaining around \u00a35m of public funds, used by the [[Skills Funding Agency]] to create apprenticeships for vulnerable young people.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://news.sky.com/story/ex-footballers-mark-aizlewood-and-paul-sugrue-jailed-for-scamming-schools-out-of-5m-11269008 |title=Ex-footballers Mark Aizlewood and Paul Sugrue jailed for scamming schools out of \u00a35m |publisher=Sky News |date=26 February 2018 |accessdate=27 July 2018}}</ref> On investigation by [[Gwent Police]] and the Fraud office of the [[Metropolitan Police]], the prosecution claimed that for every apprentice enrolled in the youth scheme, the defendants claimed funds provided by the UK government. It was also found that many students on their books did not even exist, whilst many of the youngsters that were listed lived far outside the reach of the scheme, or were doing less than four hours of study a week.<ref name=BBC42944273/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/uk-news/mark-aizlewood-facing-jail-after-11973779|title=Mark Aizlewood facing jail after being found guilty of \u00a35million football fraud|work=Daily Mirror|author=Andrew Penman|date=5 February 2018|accessdate=5 February 2018}}</ref> Aizlewood was later banned from serving as a director of any company for six years, along with fellow ex-footballer [[Paul Sugrue]] and two others.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.southwalesargus.co.uk/news/10876087.Ex_County_star_Aizelwood_banned_as_company_director/ |title=Ex-County star Aizlewood banned as company director |work=South Wales Argus |date=13 December 2013 |accessdate=1 May 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.insolvencydirect.bis.gov.uk/iesdatabase/viewdisqualdetail.asp?courtnumber=06951501 |title=Case details for Mark Aizlewood |publisher=The Insolvency Service |accessdate=5 January 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2016, Aizlewood was charged following an investigation by the [[Serious Fraud Office (United Kingdom)|Serious Fraud Office]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.southwalesargus.co.uk/news/14539526.Former_Wales_and_County_player_appears_in_court_over_fraud_allegations/ |title=Former Wales and County player appears in court over fraud allegations |work=South Wales Argus |date=6 June 2016 |accessdate=6 June 2016}}</ref> He appeared at [[Southwark Crown Court]] in November 2017.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.yorkshireeveningpost.co.uk/news/former-leeds-united-footballer-tells-5million-apprenticeship-fraud-trial-of-wife-s-suicide-1-8876361 |title=Former Leeds United footballer tells \u00a35 million apprenticeship fraud trial of wife's suicide |newspaper=Yorkshire Evening Post |author=Alex Evans |date=24 November 2017 |accessdate=16 June 2018}}</ref> In his defence, Aizlewood stated that he had neither the \"time or inclination\" to take part in the fraud due to a troubled home life with his wife Penny suffering from alcohol and drug addiction. Penny later committed suicide in 2016 following their break-up.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.walesonline.co.uk/news/wales-news/ex-wales-footballer-describes-moment-13945006 |title=Ex-Wales footballer describes the moment he learned of his wife's suicide |publisher=WalesOnline |author=Henry Vaughan |date=23 November 2017 |accessdate=14 June 2018}}</ref> In January 2018 he was convicted of one count of conspiracy to commit fraud by false representation,<ref name=\"jailedbbc\"/> after taking money in the fake apprenticeship scheme. Aizlewood was convicted alongside Sugrue and four other directors. Judge Michael Tomlinson described the case as \"very serious\" and released the defendants on bail until sentencing at a later date.<ref name=BBC42944273>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-42944273|title=Ex-player Mark Aizlewood and others guilty of football fraud|publisher=BBC Wales|date=5 February 2018|accessdate=5 February 2018}}</ref> He was later jailed for six years starting from his conviction in February 2018.<ref name=\"success\"/><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2018/feb/26/ex-footballers-mark-aizlewood-and-paul-sugrue-jailed-for-fraud |title=Ex-footballers Mark Aizlewood and Paul Sugrue jailed for fraud |newspaper=The Guardian |author=Patrick Greenfield |date=26 February 2018 |accessdate=14 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n\n===Player===\n'''Luton Town'''\n* [[Football League Second Division]] winners: 1981\u201392<ref name=\"82title\"/>\n\n'''Cardiff City'''\n\n* [[Welsh Cup]] runners-up: 1993\u201394<ref name=\"CCFC players\"/>\n\n===Manager===\n'''Carmarthen Town'''\n* [[Welsh League Cup]] Winner: [[2012\u201313 Welsh League Cup|2012\u201313]], [[2013\u201314 Welsh League Cup|2013\u201314]]<ref name=\"LCfinals\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Soccerbase}}\n\n{{1985\u201386 Football League Second Division PFA Team of the Year}}\n{{Charlton Athletic F.C. Player of the Year}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Aizlewood, Mark}}\n[[Category:1959 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Footballers from Newport, Wales]]\n[[Category:Newport County A.F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Luton Town F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Charlton Athletic F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Leeds United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Bradford City A.F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Bristol City F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Cardiff City F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Merthyr Tydfil F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Aberystwyth Town F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Cwmbr\u00e2n Town A.F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Welsh footballers]]\n[[Category:Wales under-21 international footballers]]\n[[Category:Wales international footballers]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:Cymru Premier players]]\n[[Category:Chester City F.C. non-playing staff]]\n[[Category:Welsh football managers]]\n[[Category:Carmarthen Town A.F.C. managers]]\n[[Category:Association football defenders]]\n[[Category:Cymru Premier managers]]\n[[Category:Welsh fraudsters]]\n[[Category:Welsh criminals]]\n", "text_old": "{{good article}}\n{{EngvarB|date=July 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Mark Aizlewood\n| image =\n| fullname = Mark Aizlewood<ref>{{Hugman|131|accessdate=1 November 2017}}</ref>\n| height = {{height|ft=6|in=0}}<ref name = \"Garland\">{{cite book |title=Who's Who of Welsh International Soccer Players |last1=Davies |first1=Gareth |last2=Garland |first2=Ian |year=1991 |publisher=Bridge Books |isbn=1-872424-11-2|page=11}}</ref>\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1959|10|1|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Newport, Wales|Newport]], Wales\n| position = [[Defender (association football)|Defender]]\n| youthyears1 =\n| youthclubs1 =\n| years1 = 1975\u20131978\n| years2 = 1978\u20131982\n| years3 = 1982\u20131987\n| years4 = 1987\u20131989\n| years5 = 1989\u20131990\n| years6 = 1990\u20131993\n| years7 = 1993\u20131995\n| years8 = 1995\u20131996\n| years9 = 1996\u20131997\n| years10 = 1997\u20132000\n| clubs1 = [[Newport County A.F.C.|Newport County]]\n| clubs2 = [[Luton Town F.C.|Luton Town]]\n| clubs3 = [[Charlton Athletic F.C.|Charlton Athletic]]\n| clubs4 = [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]]\n| clubs5 = [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]]\n| clubs6 = [[Bristol City F.C.|Bristol City]]\n| clubs7 = [[Cardiff City F.C.|Cardiff City]]\n| clubs8 = [[Merthyr Tydfil F.C.|Merthyr Tydfil]]\n| clubs9 = [[Aberystwyth Town F.C.|Aberystwyth Town]]\n| clubs10 = [[Cwmbran Town F.C.|Cwmbran Town]]\n| caps1 = 38 \n| caps2 = 98 \n| caps3 = 152 \n| caps4 = 70 \n| caps5 = 39 \n| caps6 = 101 \n| caps7 = 39 \n| caps8 =\n| caps9 = 30 \n| caps10 = 69 \n| goals1 = 3\n| goals2 = 2\n| goals3 = 9\n| goals4 = 3\n| goals5 = 1\n| goals6 = 3\n| goals7 = 3\n| goals8 = \n| goals9 = 1\n| goals10 = 0\n| nationalyears1 = 1979\u20131980\n| nationalteam1 = [[Wales national under-21 football team|Wales U21]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 2\n| nationalgoals1 = 0 \n| nationalyears2 = 1986\u20131994\n| nationalteam2 = [[Wales national football team|Wales]]\n| nationalcaps2 = 39 \n| nationalgoals2 = 0\n| manageryears1= 2012\u20132018\n| managerclubs1= [[Carmarthen Town A.F.C.|Carmarthen Town]]\n}}\n'''Mark Aizlewood''' (born 1 October 1959) is a Welsh former professional [[association football|footballer]] and manager.\n\nHaving started his football career at his hometown club [[Newport County A.F.C.|Newport County]], making his professional debut at the age of 16 in 1976, he went on to make over 500 appearances in the [[Football League]], most notably for [[Charlton Athletic F.C.|Charlton Athletic]], [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]] and [[Bristol City F.C.|Bristol City]], and gained 39 caps for [[Wales national football team|Wales]].<ref name=\"atz\">{{cite web |url=http://www.neilbrown.newcastlefans.com/player/markaizlewood.html |title=Mark Aizlewood |publisher=Post War English & Scottish Football League A\u2013Z Player's Database. Neil Brown |accessdate=3 June 2016}}</ref>\n\nFollowing his retirement, Aizlewood worked as an assistant manager with [[Carmarthen Town A.F.C.|Carmarthen Town]] on two occasions and later worked as assistant manager to [[Ian Rush]] at [[Chester City F.C.|Chester City]]. He also spent two years as the technical director of the [[Welsh Football Trust]], being placed in charge of developing youth football in Wales. In 2012, he returned to [[Welsh Premier League]] side Carmarthen Town as manager and lead the club to consecutive [[Welsh League Cup]] victories in 2013 and 2014. His contract as manager was terminated after he was convicted of serious fraud in February 2018.<ref name=BBC42944273/>\n\n==Early life==\nAizlewood was born in [[Newport, Wales|Newport]] and grew up in the [[Ringland, Newport|Ringland]] area. His father was a steelworker who had moved to Newport from [[Wolverhampton]].<ref name=\"goal\">{{cite news |url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-78819443.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180613234743/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-78819443.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=13 June 2018 |url-access=subscription |title=Footballer Reaches His Goal |newspaper=The Western Mail |author=Rhodri Clark |date=2 October 2001 |accessdate=13 June 2018 |via=[[HighBeam Research]]}}</ref> As a child, he attended Alway Juniors School and then [[Hartridge High School]] in Newport.<ref name=\"Argus\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.southwalesargus.co.uk/news/4738302.My_27_year_booze_battle___Mark_Aizlewood/?ref=rc |title=My 27 year booze battle |work=South Wales Argus |author=Ben Frampton |date=13 November 2009 |accessdate=5 January 2014}}</ref> His older brother [[Steve Aizlewood|Steve]] was also a professional footballer.<ref name=\"Cromwell\">{{cite web |url=http://www.southwalesargus.co.uk/sport/1876782.Don_just_misses_out_in_hero_award/ |title=Don just misses out in hero award |work=South Wales Argus |date=4 December 2007 |accessdate=13 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Playing career==\nAfter playing for local youth club Cromwell,<ref name=\"Cromwell\"/> Aizlewood joined his home-town club [[Newport County A.F.C.|Newport County]] at the age of 14, turning down an offer to join [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]].<ref name=\"oz\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ozwhitelufc.net.au/players_profiles/A/AizlewoodM.php |title=Mark Aizlewood |publisher=Oz White LUFC |accessdate=13 June 2018}}</ref> Earning a wage of five pounds per week to cover expenses, he made his professional debut two years later at the age of just 16, whilst he was still attending school.<ref name=\"CCFC players\">{{Cite book | title = The Who's Who of Cardiff City | first = Dean | last = Hayes| publisher = Breedon Books | year = 2006 | p=11 | location=Derby | isbn= 1-85983-462-0}}</ref> He played for Newport for three years, leaving in 1978 to join [[Luton Town F.C.|Luton Town]] for a fee of \u00a350,000, becoming [[David Pleat]]'s first signing at the club.<ref name=\"Argus\"/> After four seasons at Luton, winning the [[Football League Second Division|Second Division]] title in his final year,<ref name=\"82title\">{{cite web |url=https://www.pressreader.com/uk/the-football-league-paper/20140928/282454232214951 |title=Luton Town 1981\u201382 Division Two Champions |publisher=The Football League Paper |author=Neil Fissler |date=28 September 2014 |accessdate=14 June 2018 |via=Press Reader}}</ref> he moved on to [[Charlton Athletic F.C.|Charlton Athletic]] in 1982, again for a fee of \u00a350,000.<ref name=hattersheroes/> He was later appointed club captain and was named the club's player of the year for both the [[1984\u201385 Football League|1984\u201385]] and [[1985\u201386 Football League|1985\u201386]] seasons.<ref name=\"CCFC players\"/>\n\nIn 1987, Charlton received an offer of \u00a3200,000 from [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]] for Aizlewood. Despite resistance from manager [[Lennie Lawrence]], Aizlewood decided to accept the move as the club were then managed by one of his boyhood idols, [[Billy Bremner]].<ref name=\"Hewore\">{{cite web |url=http://www.sheridan-dictates.com/he-wore-the-white-shirt-mark-aizlewood.php |title=Mark Aizlewood |publisher=He wore the shirt |accessdate=3 June 2016}}</ref> Signed as a replacement for [[Ian Snodin]], who had left the club to join [[Everton F.C.|Everton]], he made his debut in a goalless draw with [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]] on 7 February 1987. He became influential almost immediately, missing just one league match for the rest of the season as Leeds finished in fourth position and went on to reach the play-off final, losing to his former club Charlton.<ref name=\"Hewore\"/> Aizlewood was also appointed club captain. However, [[1987\u201388 Football League|the following season]], Leeds struggled to repeat their good form, following the sales of [[Andy Ritchie (English footballer)|Andy Ritchie]] and [[Ian Baird]], and Bremner was sacked from his position as manager. Aizlewood himself became a target for some fans frustration and during a [[Football League Second Division|Second Division]] clash with [[Walsall F.C.|Walsall]] at the end of the [[1988\u201389 Football League|1988\u201389]] season, he reacted to jeers by Leeds' own fans by displaying a [[V sign]], an offensive gesture in the UK,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bbcamerica.com/anglophenia/2013/01/10-things-americans-dont-realize-are-offensive-to-brits |title=10 Things That Americans Don't Realize are Offensive to Brits |publisher=BBC America |author=Ruth Margolis |accessdate=26 July 2018}}</ref> to the crowd after scoring in the closing stages to make the score 1\u20130.<ref name=\"Hewore\"/> Leeds manager [[Howard Wilkinson]] quickly substituted Aizlewood, who blew kisses to the crowd and removed his captain's armband,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.yorkshireeveningpost.co.uk/sport/leeds-united/latest-whites-news/action-replay-aizlewood-goal-salute-was-no-mark-of-respect-1-2210982 |title=Aizlewood salute no Mark of respect |work=Yorkshire Evening Post |date=1 May 2009 |accessdate=5 January 2014}}</ref> for [[David Batty]]. He reacted furiously toward Wilkinson and refused a seat on the bench, returning straight to the dressing room.<ref name=\"Sheridan\">{{cite web |url=http://www.sheridan-dictates.com/he-wore-the-white-shirt-mark-aizlewood.php |title=Mark Aizlewood |publisher=Sheridan Dictates |accessdate=26 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nHe left the club soon after in a \u00a3125,000 move to [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]],<ref name=\"Rush\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.thefootballnetwork.net/main/s418/st70223.htm |title=Ian Rush's assistant, Mark Aizlewood leaves |publisher=The Football Network |author=Chris Thompson |date=5 April 2005 |accessdate=5 January 2014}}</ref> with Aizlewood keen to remain in Yorkshire where his family was settled, reuniting Aizlewood with his former manager at international level, [[Terry Yorath]]. He spent one season at [[Valley Parade]], making 39 league appearances, before moving on to [[Bristol City F.C.|Bristol City]].<ref name=\"Sheridan\"/> He spent three seasons with Bristol, making over 100 appearances in all competitions and scoring three times.<ref name=\"atz\"/>\n\nIn 1993, he returned to Wales to sign for [[Cardiff City F.C.|Cardiff City]]. In his one full season at [[Ninian Park]], the club narrowly avoided relegation to [[Football League Third Division|Division Three]] but did reach the final of the [[Welsh Cup]], losing 2\u20131 to [[Barry Town United F.C.|Barry Town]]. He was also named man of the match in the club's 1\u20130 FA Cup Fourth Round victory over [[Premier League]] side [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] in January 1994.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.walesonline.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/aizlewood-one-citys-great-fa-2408059 |title=Aizlewood: one of City's great FA Cup triumphs |publisher=WalesOnline |date=4 January 2005 |accessdate=14 June 2018}}</ref> During the following season, Aizlewood decided to leave the club in order to take up a player-coach role at [[Merthyr Tydfil F.C.|Merthyr Tydfil]].<ref name=\"CCFC players\"/> He later finished his career with spells at [[Welsh Premier League]] sides [[Aberystwyth Town F.C.|Aberystwyth Town]] and [[Cwmbran Town F.C.|Cwmbran Town]] before retiring in 2000.<ref name=hattersheroes/>\n\n==International career==\n\nHaving previously captained Wales at youth level,<ref name=\"oz\"/> Aizlewood played twice for the [[Wales national under-21 football team|Wales under-21 side]], making his debut in a 1\u20130 defeat to [[England national under-21 football team|England]] on 6 February 1979 before winning his second cap a year later in September 1980 in a 2\u20130 victory over the [[Netherlands national under-21 football team|Netherlands]].<ref name=\"11v11\">{{cite web |url=https://www.11v11.com/players/mark-aizlewood-33981/ |title=Mark Aizlewood |work=11v11.com |publisher=AFS Enterprises |accessdate=14 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nAizlewood made his debut for the [[Wales national football team|Wales]] senior side on 25 February 1986, during a 2\u20131 victory over [[Saudi Arabia national football team|Saudi Arabia]] in [[Riyadh]].<ref name=\"11v11\"/> His last appearance came on 14 December 1994 as Wales lost 3\u20130 to [[Bulgaria national football team|Bulgaria]] in a [[UEFA Euro 1996|Euro 96]] qualifier at [[Cardiff Arms Park]]. He finished his career having won 39 caps for Wales without scoring.<ref name=\"11v11\"/>\n\n==Management and coaching career==\n\n===FAW Trust===\nIn 2001, Aizlewood was appointed as technical director of the [[Welsh Football Trust]], a governing body of the [[Football Association of Wales]] (FAW), following the resignation of Mike Rigg,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-79495135.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180613234503/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-79495135.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=13 June 2018 |url-access=subscription |title=Aizlewood Is Appointed as New Technical Director |newspaper=The Western Mail |author=Ian Hunt |date=27 October 2001 |accessdate=13 June 2018 |via=HighBeam Research}}</ref> a role which he described as his \"dream job\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-79730617.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090525223808/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-79730617.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=25 May 2009 |url-access=subscription |title=Aizlewood Relishes New Task of Shaking Up Welsh Football from Grass Roots |newspaper=Wales on Sunday |author=Paul Abbandonato |date=4 November 2001 |accessdate=14 June 2018 |via=HighBeam Research}}</ref> However, despite increasing the trust's coaching revenues by 75 per cent during his time in charge, he was sacked in December 2003 following an altercation with a BBC camera crew and presenter.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.walesonline.co.uk/news/wales-news/soccer-pundit-sacked-bbc-after-2475591 |title=Soccer pundit sacked by BBC after row |publisher=WalesOnline |date=25 August 2003 |accessdate=13 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-111267386.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180613234637/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-111267386.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=13 June 2018 |url-access=subscription |title=Aizlewood plans to fight after job axe |newspaper=The Western Mail |author=Paul Abbandonato |date=11 December 2003 |accessdate=13 June 2018 |via=HighBeam Research}}</ref> During filming of an interview BBC investigative programme ''X-Ray'', Aizlewood reportedly attempted to forcibly remove a tape from a camera and chased the crew from the trust's offices in Cardiff. He was also accused of assaulting presenter Jane Harvey by \"grabbing her around the neck and pushing her down a flight of steps\" with Harvey describing him as \"berserk\". He was later convicted of assaulting Harvey and ordered to pay a fine of \u00a31,800 and his conduct was described by the judge as \"entirely inappropriate.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/wales/3827067.stm |title=Ex-footballer guilty of presenter attack |publisher=BBC News |date=21 June 2004 |accessdate=5 January 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Chester City===\nAizlewood had a spell on the coaching staff of [[Carmarthen Town A.F.C.|Carmarthen Town]] during [[2003-04 in English football|2003\u201304]], but left to become assistant manager to [[Ian Rush]] at [[Chester City F.C.|Chester City]] for [[2004-05 in English football|2004\u201305]].<ref name=\"carmarthenhistory\">{{cite news |url=http://www.carmarthentownafc.net/history.htm |title=Hanes Y Clwb / Club History |publisher=Carmarthen Town A.F.C. |accessdate=22 May 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090119192957/http://carmarthentownafc.net/history.htm |archivedate=19 January 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The club made a strong start to the season, embarking on a ten match unbeaten run,<ref name=\"shot\">{{cite web |url=https://www.chesterchronicle.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/rush-aims-parting-shot-after-5285380 |title=Rush aims parting shot after quitting Chester job |work=Chester Chronicle |date=6 April 2005 |accessdate=27 July 2018}}</ref> and Rush was linked to the vacant Wales job but a difficult period in the second half of the season, winning just 2 out of 10 matches, saw the club fall down the table and pressure grew on Rush and his management team.<ref name=\"shot\"/><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/2389422/Rush-rejects-Wales-job.html |title=Rush rejects Wales job |newspaper=The Telegraph |date=2 November 2004 |accessdate=27 July 2018}}</ref> On 4 April 2005, Aizlewood was sacked by Chester chairman [[Stephen Vaughan, Sr|Stephen Vaughan]] without Rush's knowledge.<ref name=\"Rush\"/> Rush himself resigned two days later in protest of the decision, stating \"Loyalty is vital in football and I am a loyal person. When a valued member of my team is dismissed against my wishes, I have no option but to follow my principles.\" When the pair left the club, Chester were nine points clear of the relegation zone, having been bottom of the table when they arrived.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/c/chester/4415035.stm |title=Rush walks out as Chester manager |publisher=BBC Sport |date=6 April 2005 |accessdate=4 June 2016}}</ref> Rush later described Aizlewood as \"one of the best coaches I have worked with.\"<ref name=\"success\">{{cite web |url=https://www.walesonline.co.uk/news/wales-news/success-gambling-depression-drink-crime-14389597 |title=Success, gambling, depression, drink and crime: the fall of Mark Aizlewood |publisher=WalesOnline |author=Robert Harries |date=9 March 2018 |accessdate=14 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Carmarthen Town===\nAizlewood worked as an [[Sports agent|agent]] briefly after leaving Chester as well as managing his business interests.<ref name=\"hattersheroes\">{{cite book | title=Hatters Heroes | publisher=Roger Wash | first= Roger | last= Wash | year=2008 | isbn=978-0-9560832-0-3}}</ref> Having considered leaving football, he was handed his first job as manager in January 2012 by Jeff Thomas, chairman of Carmarthen Town.<ref name=\"success\"/> Returning to the club to replace Tomi Morgan, having previously worked there as assistant manager to Andrew York and [[Deryn Brace]] in separate spells. The club were joint bottom of the Welsh Premier League on his appointment,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.wpl.cymru/news/WPL82318.ink |title=Aizlewood handed task of saving Carmarthen |publisher=Welsh Premier League |date=7 January 2012 |accessdate=14 June 2018}}</ref> along with [[Newtown A.F.C.|Newtown]], but Aizlewood was able to steer them away from relegation. The following year, Aizlewood lead the club to the [[Welsh League Cup]] final, defeating [[The New Saints F.C.|The New Saints]] on penalties to claim the trophy for only the second time in the club's history. They retained the trophy in the 2013\u201314 season, defeating [[Bala Town F.C.|Bala Town]] in the final.<ref name=\"LCfinals\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesw/walleagcuphist.html |title=Wales - List of League Cup finals |publisher=Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation |author=Jo\u00e3o Nunes |accessdate=4 June 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2014, Aizlewood attempted to register himself as a player for Carmarthen, at the age of 55, following an injury crisis at the club prior to a league fixture against [[Rhyl F.C.|Rhyl]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/29911967 |title=Mark Aizlewood: Carmarthen Town boss could play aged 55 |publisher=BBC Sport |date=5 November 2014 |accessdate=4 June 2016}}</ref> However, the plans were ended following a fire at Rhyl's ground which postponed the fixture.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/29935755 |title=Mark Aizlewood: Carmarthen Town boss comeback scuppered by fire |publisher=BBC Sport |date=6 November 2014 |accessdate=4 June 2016}}</ref> He was sacked by the club in February 2018 following his fraud conviction after six years in charge.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.walesonline.co.uk/news/wales-news/carmarthen-town-sack-manager-mark-14248466 |title=Carmarthen Town sack manager Mark Aizlewood after fraud conviction |publisher=WalesOnline |author=Ian Lewis |date=5 February 2018 |accessdate=14 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n\n===Addiction battle===\nAizlewood speaks [[Welsh language|Welsh]],<ref name=\"welshspeaker\">{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/welsh-speak-up-for-their-ancient-tongue-1311562.html |title=Welsh speak up for their ancient tongue |author=Tony Heath |work=The Independent |date=26 August 1996 |accessdate=22 May 2009}}</ref> having taken up lessons during a long injury spell as a player. After becoming proficient with the language he entered the Welsh Learner of the Year competition at the [[National Eisteddfod of Wales]] in [[Llandeilo]] where he was named as the winner.<ref name=\"goal\"/> He released his Welsh language autobiography in 2009, entitled ''Amddiffyn fy Hun'' (Defending Myself) in which he revealed his 27-year-long battle with alcoholism and gambling and contemplating suicide. All proceeds from the book were donated to former England player [[Tony Adams (footballer)|Tony Adams]] Sporting Chance charity.<ref name=\"Argus\"/> His alcohol problem began as an 18 year old, during his time at Luton Town where he found himself with a large disposable income. Remarking on this period, Aizlewood has stated: \"I was making a very good living [...] sometimes I didn't drink for two or three weeks, but then I'd drink for three of four days in one go.\" At his worst, Aizlewood was able to drink a bottle of brandy and 20 pints of lager in one session and still stand. He also developed a gambling addiction and has admitted to losing up to \u00a330,000 in a single day.<ref name=\"Argus\"/> In his book, Aizlewood confessed to once nearly attempting suicide during a trip to [[Rome]] in 2003 due to the severity of his addictions. He stated that on 14 February, he had stood on a motorway bridge in the Italian capital in the early hours of the morning and considered jumping 50&nbsp;ft to the carriageway below,<ref name=\"Argus\"/> commenting \" I didn't have an ounce of fear as I stood on the small wall and looked down at the cars speeding along the road 50ft below me, because I only had one intention: to jump.\"<ref name=\"success\"/>\n\n===Punditry===\nFollowing his retirement from playing, Aizlewood worked as a [[pundit]] for [[BBC Wales]], covering Welsh football, where he developed a reputation as an outspoken critic. He was particularly critical of [[Swansea City A.F.C.|Swansea City]] and their decision to sign several foreign players whilst playing in the lower leagues.<ref name=\"Hostilevetch\">{{cite web |url=http://www.walesonline.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/aizlewood---no-thoughts-hostile-2410226 |title=Aizlewood - no thoughts of hostile Vetch |publisher=WalesOnline |date=27 January 2005 |accessdate=4 June 2016}}</ref> Swansea forward [[Giovanni Savarese]], along with other players, was branded unreliable by Aizlewood and, following Savarese being dismissed for a deliberate elbow on [[Wrexham A.F.C.|Wrexham]] defender [[Mark McGregor]] during the 2001 [[FAW Premier Cup]] final, Aizlewood was accused of racism after calling Savarese a \"coward\" and stating \"but that's foreigners for you\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Football%3A+'Coward'+Gio+under+attack+by+Aizlewood%3B+Swansea+City+0...-a074503594 |title=\"Coward\" Gio under attack by Aizlewood |work=Daily Mirror |author=Tony Rees |date=15 May 2001 |accessdate=4 June 2016 |via=The Free Library}}</ref> His outspoken views of Swansea and their players made him a target for fans of the club and, in October 2002, Aizlewood was attacked by a group of Swansea fans, after commentating at a game against [[Rochdale A.F.C.|Rochdale]] at [[Vetch Field]], who pushed him into a gate, causing him to suffer grazing to his eye. BBC Wales head of sport, Nigel Walker demanded that the club would assure Aizlewood's safety at future matches following the incident.<ref name=\"Hostilevetch\"/>\n\n==Fraud conviction==\nAfter an investigation by various newspapers, in 2012, Aizlewood was one of three men arrested in connection with allegations of fraud regarding \u00a31.6m of government funds that had been given to Luis Michael Training Ltd based in Newport, a company where Aizlewood was serving as a director.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/law/2012/may/17/sfo-football-skills-fraud-probe |title=SFO make arrests in football apprenticeship investigation |work=The Guardian |date=17 May 2012 |accessdate=5 January 2014}}</ref> The company offered football apprenticeships, promising to provide full-time training in football coaching as well as work experience and a \u00a395 weekly salary, to up to 3,800 students.<ref name=\"jailedbbc\">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-43196467 |title=Mark Aizlewood jailed over football apprenticeship fraud |publisher=BBC News |date=26 February 2018 |accessdate=27 July 2018}}</ref> However, the company focused on targeting young players from youth clubs between 2009 and 2011, fraudulently obtaining around \u00a35m of public funds, used by the [[Skills Funding Agency]] to create apprenticeships for vulnerable young people.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://news.sky.com/story/ex-footballers-mark-aizlewood-and-paul-sugrue-jailed-for-scamming-schools-out-of-5m-11269008 |title=Ex-footballers Mark Aizlewood and Paul Sugrue jailed for scamming schools out of \u00a35m |publisher=Sky News |date=26 February 2018 |accessdate=27 July 2018}}</ref> On investigation by [[Gwent Police]] and the Fraud office of the [[Metropolitan Police]], the prosecution claimed that for every apprentice enrolled in the youth scheme, the defendants claimed funds provided by the UK government. It was also found that many students on their books did not even exist, whilst many of the youngsters that were listed lived far outside the reach of  the scheme, or were doing less than four hours of study a week.<ref name=BBC42944273/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/uk-news/mark-aizlewood-facing-jail-after-11973779|title=Mark Aizlewood facing jail after being found guilty of \u00a35million football fraud|work=Daily Mirror|author=Andrew Penman|date=5 February 2018|accessdate=5 February 2018}}</ref> Aizlewood was later banned from serving as a director of any company for six years, along with fellow ex-footballer [[Paul Sugrue]] and two others.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.southwalesargus.co.uk/news/10876087.Ex_County_star_Aizelwood_banned_as_company_director/ |title=Ex-County star Aizlewood banned as company director |work=South Wales Argus |date=13 December 2013 |accessdate=1 May 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.insolvencydirect.bis.gov.uk/iesdatabase/viewdisqualdetail.asp?courtnumber=06951501 |title=Case details for Mark Aizlewood |publisher=The Insolvency Service |accessdate=5 January 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2016, Aizlewood was charged following an investigation by the [[Serious Fraud Office (United Kingdom)|Serious Fraud Office]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.southwalesargus.co.uk/news/14539526.Former_Wales_and_County_player_appears_in_court_over_fraud_allegations/ |title=Former Wales and County player appears in court over fraud allegations |work=South Wales Argus |date=6 June 2016 |accessdate=6 June 2016}}</ref> He appeared at [[Southwark Crown Court]] in November 2017.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.yorkshireeveningpost.co.uk/news/former-leeds-united-footballer-tells-5million-apprenticeship-fraud-trial-of-wife-s-suicide-1-8876361 |title=Former Leeds United footballer tells \u00a35 million apprenticeship fraud trial of wife's suicide |newspaper=Yorkshire Evening Post |author=Alex Evans |date=24 November 2017 |accessdate=16 June 2018}}</ref> In his defence, Aizlewood stated that he had neither the \"time or inclination\" to take part in the fraud due to a troubled home life with his wife Penny suffering from alcohol and drug addiction. Penny later committed suicide in 2016 following their break-up.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.walesonline.co.uk/news/wales-news/ex-wales-footballer-describes-moment-13945006 |title=Ex-Wales footballer describes the moment he learned of his wife's suicide |publisher=WalesOnline |author=Henry Vaughan |date=23 November 2017 |accessdate=14 June 2018}}</ref> In January 2018 he was convicted of one count of conspiracy to commit fraud by false representation,<ref name=\"jailedbbc\"/> after taking money in the fake apprenticeship scheme. Aizlewood was convicted alongside Sugrue and four other directors. Judge Michael Tomlinson described the case as \"very serious\" and released the defendants on bail until sentencing at a later date.<ref name=BBC42944273>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-42944273|title=Ex-player Mark Aizlewood and others guilty of football fraud|publisher=BBC Wales|date=5 February 2018|accessdate=5 February 2018}}</ref> He was later jailed for six years starting from his conviction in February 2018.<ref name=\"success\"/><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2018/feb/26/ex-footballers-mark-aizlewood-and-paul-sugrue-jailed-for-fraud |title=Ex-footballers Mark Aizlewood and Paul Sugrue jailed for fraud |newspaper=The Guardian |author=Patrick Greenfield |date=26 February 2018 |accessdate=14 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n\n===Player===\n'''Luton Town'''\n* [[Football League Second Division]] winners: 1981\u201392<ref name=\"82title\"/>\n\n'''Cardiff City'''\n\n* [[Welsh Cup]] runners-up: 1993\u201394<ref name=\"CCFC players\"/>\n\n===Manager===\n'''Carmarthen Town'''\n* [[Welsh League Cup]] Winner: [[2012\u201313 Welsh League Cup|2012\u201313]], [[2013\u201314 Welsh League Cup|2013\u201314]]<ref name=\"LCfinals\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Soccerbase}}\n\n{{1985\u201386 Football League Second Division PFA Team of the Year}}\n{{Charlton Athletic F.C. Player of the Year}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Aizlewood, Mark}}\n[[Category:1959 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Footballers from Newport, Wales]]\n[[Category:Newport County A.F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Luton Town F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Charlton Athletic F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Leeds United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Bradford City A.F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Bristol City F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Cardiff City F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Merthyr Tydfil F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Aberystwyth Town F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Cwmbr\u00e2n Town A.F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Welsh footballers]]\n[[Category:Wales under-21 international footballers]]\n[[Category:Wales international footballers]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:Cymru Premier players]]\n[[Category:Chester City F.C. non-playing staff]]\n[[Category:Welsh football managers]]\n[[Category:Carmarthen Town A.F.C. managers]]\n[[Category:Association football defenders]]\n[[Category:Cymru Premier managers]]\n[[Category:Welsh fraudsters]]\n[[Category:Welsh criminals]]\n", "name_user": "Robby.is.on", "label": "safe", "comment": "Minor corrections.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mark_Aizlewood"}
{"title_page": "Millbank Prison", "text_new": "[[File:Millbank Thomas Hosmer Shepherd pub 1829.jpg|thumb|upright=1.4|Millbank Prison in the 1820s]]\n'''Millbank Prison''' was a prison in [[Millbank]], [[Westminster]], [[London]], originally constructed as the National Penitentiary, and which for part of its history served as a holding facility for convicted prisoners before they were [[Penal transportation|transported to Australia]]. It was opened in 1816 and closed in 1890.\n\n==Construction==\n[[File:Millbank Prison Plan.jpg|thumb|right|upright=1.2|Plan of Millbank Prison]]\nThe site at Millbank was originally purchased in 1799 from the [[James Cecil, 1st Marquess of Salisbury|Marquess of Salisbury]] for \u00a312,000 by the philosopher [[Jeremy Bentham]], acting on behalf of [[the Crown]], for the erection of his proposed [[Panopticon]] prison as Britain's new National Penitentiary.<ref name=Timbs>{{cite book|first=John|last=Timbs |author-link=John Timbs|title=Curiosities of London: Exhibiting the Most Rare and Remarkable Objects of Interest in the Metropolis|url=https://archive.org/stream/curiositiesoflon00timbrich#page/697/mode/1up|year=1855|publisher=D. Bogue|page=697}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Semple |first=Janet |year=1993 |title=Bentham's Prison: a Study of the Panopticon Penitentiary |place=Oxford |publisher=Clarendon Press |isbn=0-19827387-8 |pages=218\u201322 }}</ref> After various changes in circumstance, the Panopticon plan was abandoned in 1812. Proposals for the National Penitentiary continued, however, and were given a legislative basis in the [[Penitentiary House, etc. Act 1812|Penitentiary House, etc. Act]] of 1812 (52 Geo. 3 c. 44). An architectural competition for a new prison building on the Millbank site attracted 43 entrants: the winning design was that of William Williams, drawing master at the [[Royal Military College, Sandhurst]]. Williams' basic plan was adapted by a practising architect, [[Thomas Hardwick]], who began construction in the same year. Hardwick resigned in 1813, and John Harvey took over the role. Harvey was dismissed in turn in 1815, and replaced by [[Robert Smirke (architect)|Robert Smirke]], who brought the project to completion in 1821.<ref name=\"handbook\">{{cite book |last=Cunningham |first=Peter |authorlink=Peter Cunningham (British writer) |chapter=Millbank Prison |title=Hand-book of London: past and present |edition=2nd |location=London |publisher=John Murray |year=1850 |pages=[https://archive.org/details/handbookoflondon00cunn/page/337 337]\u201338 |url=https://archive.org/details/handbookoflondon00cunn }}</ref> Further legislation was passed in the form of the [[Millbank Penitentiary Act 1816|Millbank Penitentiary Act]] of 1816 (56 Geo. 3 c. 63).\n\nThe marshy site on which the prison stood meant that the builders experienced problems of [[Groundwater-related subsidence|subsidence]] from the outset, and explains the succession of architects. Smirke finally resolved the difficulty by introducing a highly innovative [[concrete]] [[Floating raft system|raft]] to provide a secure foundation. However, this added considerably to the construction costs, which eventually totalled \u00a3500,000, more than twice the original estimate and equivalent to \u00a3500 per cell.<ref name=Timbs />\n\n==History==\nThe first prisoners, all women, were admitted on 26 June 1816. The first men arrived in January 1817. The prison held 103 men and 109 women by the end of 1817, and 452 men and 326 women by late 1822. Sentences of five to ten years in the National Penitentiary were offered as an alternative to [[Penal transportation|transportation]] to those thought most likely to reform. \n\nIn addition to the problems of construction, the marshy site fostered disease, to which the prisoners had little immunity owing to their extremely poor diet. In 1818 the authorities engaged Dr [[Alexander Copland Hutchison]] of Westminster Dispensary as Medical Supervisor, to oversee the health of the inmates.<ref>''Parliamentary Papers 1780\u20131849'', vol. 5, 1825: \"The General Penitentiary at Millbank\".</ref> In 1822&ndash;23 an epidemic swept through the prison, which seems to have comprised a mixture of [[dysentery]], [[scurvy]], [[Depression (mood)|depression]] and other disorders.<ref>Evans 1982, p. 249.</ref> The decision was eventually taken to evacuate the buildings for several months: the female prisoners were released, and the male prisoners temporarily transferred to the [[List of British prison hulks|prison hulks]] at [[Woolwich]], where their health improved.\n\nThe design of Millbank also turned out to be unsatisfactory. The network of corridors was so labyrinthine that even the warders got lost;<ref>Griffiths 1884, p. 27.</ref> and the ventilation system allowed sound to carry, so that prisoners could communicate between cells. The annual running costs turned out to be an unsupportable \u00a316,000.\n\nIn view of these problems, the decision was eventually taken to build a new \"model prison\" at [[Pentonville (HM Prison)|Pentonville]], which opened in 1842 and took over Millbank's role as the National Penitentiary. By an Act of Parliament of 1843, Millbank's status was downgraded, and it became a holding depot for convicts prior to [[Penal transportation|transportation]]. Every person sentenced to transportation was sent to Millbank first, where they were held for three months before their final destination was decided. By 1850, around 4,000 people were condemned annually to transportation from the UK.<ref name=\"handbook\"/> Prisoners awaiting transportation were kept in solitary confinement and restricted to silence for the first half of their sentence.\n\nLarge-scale transportation ended in 1853 (although the practice continued on a reduced scale until 1867); and Millbank then became an ordinary local prison, and from 1870 a military prison. By 1886 it had ceased to hold inmates, and it closed in 1890.<ref>Brodie ''et al.'' 2002, p. 60.</ref> Demolition began in 1892, and continued sporadically until 1903.\n\n==Description==\n[[File:Burial ground at Millbank Prison.JPG|thumb|The prison's burial ground, with the [[Houses of Parliament]] in the background. The image was published in 1862.]]\n[[File:Millbank Cassell's large-scale map of London c 1867.jpg|thumb|Map of 1867, showing the prison and its surroundings]]\nThe plan of the prison comprised a circular chapel at the centre of the site, surrounded by a three-storey hexagon made up of the governor's quarters, administrative offices and laundries, surrounded in turn by six pentagons of cell blocks. The buildings of each pentagon were set around a cluster of five small courtyards (with a [[watchtower]] at the centre) used as airing-yards, and in which prisoners undertook labour.<ref>Griffiths 1884, p. 26.</ref> The three outer angles of each pentagon were distinguished by tall circular towers, described in 1862 as \"[[Martello tower|Martello]]-like\": these served in part as watchtowers, but their primary purpose was to contain staircases and [[Flush toilet|water-closets]].<ref name=MayhewBinny>Mayhew and Binny 1862.</ref><ref>Holford 1828, plan of prison.</ref> The third and fourth pentagons (those to the north-west, furthest from the entrance) were used to house female prisoners, and the remaining four for male prisoners.\n\nIn the ''Handbook of London'' in 1850 the prison was described as follows:<ref name=\"handbook\"/>\n{{quote|A mass of brickwork equal to a fortress, on the left bank of the [[Thames]], close to [[Vauxhall Bridge]]; erected on ground bought in 1799 of the Marquis of Salisbury, and established pursuant to [[Penitentiary House, etc. Act 1812|52 Geo. III., c. 44]], passed Aug 20th, 1812. It was designed by Jeremy Bentham [factually incorrect], to whom the fee-simple of the ground was conveyed, and is said to have cost the enormous sum of half a million sterling. The external walls form an irregular octagon, and enclose upwards of sixteen acres of land. Its ground-plan resembles a wheel, the governor's house occupying a circle in the centre, from which radiate six piles of building, terminating externally in towers. The ground on which it stands is raised but little above the river, and was at one time considered unhealthy. It was first named \"The Penitentiary\", or \"Penitentiary House for London and Middlesex\", and was called \"The Millbank Prison\" pursuant to [[Millbank Prison Act 1843|6 & 7 of Victoria, c. 26]]. It is the largest prison in London. Every male and female convict sentenced to [[Penal transportation|transportation]] in Great Britain is sent to Millbank previous to the sentence being executed. Here they remain about three months under the close inspection of the three inspectors of the prison, at the end of which time the inspectors report to the Home Secretary, and recommend the place of transportation. The number of persons in Great Britain and Ireland condemned to transportation every year amounts to about 4000. So far as the accommodation of the prison permits, the [[separate system]] is adopted.}}\n\nEach cell had a single window (looking into the pentagon courtyard), and was equipped with a washing tub, a wooden stool, a hammock and bedding, and books including a Bible, a prayer-book, a hymn-book, an arithmetic-book, a work entitled ''Home and Common Things'', and publications of the [[Society for Promoting Christian Knowledge]].<ref name=MayhewBinny/>\n\n[[Irish republicanism|Irish republican]] prisoner [[Michael Davitt]], who was held briefly at Millbank in 1870, described the experience: \n\n{{quote|[[Big Ben|Westminster Clock]] is not far distant from the penitentiary, so that its every stroke is as distinctly heard in each cell as if it were situated in one of the prison yards. At each quarter of an hour, day and night it chimes a bar of the \"[[Old 100th|Old Hundredth]]\" and those solemn tones strike on the ears of the lonely listeners like the voice of some monster spirit singing the funeral dirge of Time.<ref>{{cite book |title=Irish political prisoners: speeches of John O'Connor Power in the House of Commons on the subject of amnesty, &c., and a statement by Mr. Michael Davitt on prison treatment |first1=John O'Connor |last1=Power |first2=Michael |last2=Davitt |place=London |year=1878 |page=52 }}</ref>}}\n\n==Later development of the site==\n[[File:OS Millbank Tate etc 2.jpg|thumb|The site of the prison in 1916, after redevelopment. Its outline is still visible in the pattern of streets and buildings.]]\nAs the prison was progressively demolished its site was redeveloped. The principal new buildings erected were the National Gallery of British Art (now [[Tate Britain]]), which opened in 1897; the [[Royal Army Medical School]], the buildings of which were adapted in 2005 to become the [[Chelsea College of Art & Design]]; and{{spaced ndash}}using the original bricks of the prison{{spaced ndash}}the [[Millbank#Notable buildings|Millbank Estate]], a housing estate built by the [[London County Council]] (LCC) between 1897 and 1902. The estate comprises 17 buildings, each named after a distinguished painter, and is [[Listed building#England and Wales|Grade II listed]].\n\n==Surviving remains==\n[[File:Pimlico buttress 1.jpg|thumb|upright|left|Surviving [[bollard]]]]\n[[File:Millbank Prison Ditch.jpg|thumb|Surviving perimeter ditch]]\n\nA large circular [[bollard]] stands by the river with the inscription: \"Near this site stood Millbank Prison which was opened in 1816 and closed in 1890. This buttress stood at the head of the river steps from which, until 1867, prisoners sentenced to transportation embarked on their journey to Australia.\"\n\nPart of the perimeter ditch of the prison survives running between Cureton Street and John Islip Street. It is now used as a clothes-drying area for residents of Wilkie House.\n\nArchaeological investigations in the late 1990s and early 2000s on the sites of Chelsea College of Art and Design and Tate Britain recorded significant remains of the foundations of the external pentagon walls of the prison, of parts of the inner hexagon, of two of the courtyard watchtowers, of drainage [[culvert]]s, and of Smirke's concrete raft.<ref>Edwards 2007.</ref><ref>Edwards 2010.</ref>\n\nThe granite gate piers at the entrance of Purbeck House, High Street, [[Swanage]] in Dorset, and a granite bollard next to the gate, are thought by [[English Heritage]] to be possibly from Millbank Prison.<ref>{{NHLE|num=1119904 |desc=Gate piers and bollard at entrance to Purbeck House, High Street|grade=II|accessdate=24 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Cultural references==\n[[Charles Dickens]] describes the prison in chapter 52 (\"Obstinacy\") of his novel, ''[[Bleak House]]'' (1852\u20133). One of the characters is put into custody there, and other characters go to visit him. Esther Summerson, one of the book's narrators, gives a brief description of its layout.<ref>{{cite book |first=Charles |last=Dickens |authorlink=Charles Dickens |title=Bleak House |location=London |publisher=Chapman & Hall |date=1853 |page=563 |url=https://archive.org/stream/bleakhouse00dickiala#page/562/mode/2up }}</ref>\n\nIn [[Henry James]]'s [[Literary realism|realist]] novel ''[[The Princess Casamassima]]'' (1886) the prison is the \"primal scene\" of Hyacinth Robinson's life: the visit to his mother, dying in the infirmary, is described in chapter 3. James visited Millbank on 12 December 1884 to gain material.<ref>''Henry James letters'', edited by Leon Edel, Vol. 3: 1883\u20131895, Cambridge, Mass.: Belknap Press of Harvard University Press; London: Macmillan, 1980, page 61.</ref> \n\nSir [[Arthur Conan Doyle]] in chapter 8 of ''[[The Sign of the Four|The Sign of Four]]'' (1890) refers to [[Sherlock Holmes|Holmes]] and [[Dr. Watson|Watson]] crossing the Thames from the house of Mordecai Smith and landing by the Millbank Penitentiary.\n\nIn chapter 8 of Conan Doyle's ''[[The Lost World (Conan Doyle novel)|The Lost World]]'' (1912), [[Professor Challenger]] says that he dislikes walking along the Thames as it is always sad to see one's final destination. Challenger means that he expects to be buried at [[Westminster Abbey]], but his rival Professor Summerlee responds sardonically that he understands that Millbank Prison has been demolished.\n\nThe prison is a key location within [[Sarah Waters]]' novel ''[[Affinity (novel)|Affinity]]'' (1999).\n\nThe prison, Bentham's philosophy surrounding it, and a fictionalized account of Smirke's role in its construction play a key part in the plot of horror fiction podcast [[The Magnus Archives]] by Jonathan Sims.<ref>{{cite podcast|url=http://rustyquill.com/the-magnus-archives/|title=Panopticon|website=The Magnus Archives|publisher=Rusty Quill|date=17 October 2019|access-date=14 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n*[[List of demolished buildings and structures in London]]\n*[[Convicts in Australia]]\n*[[Penal transportation]]\n*[[Separate system]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{Cite book |first1=Allan |last1=Brodie |first2=Jane |last2=Croom |first3=James O. |last3=Davies |title=English Prisons: an architectural history |place =Swindon |publisher=English Heritage |year=2002 |ISBN=1-873592-53-1 |url=http://archaeologydataservice.ac.uk/archives/view/eh_monographs_2014/contents.cfm?mono=1089057}}\n* {{Cite journal |first=Catherine |last=Edwards |title=The Millbank Penitentiary: excavations at the Chelsea School of Art and Design |journal=London Archaeologist |volume=11.7 |year=2007 |pages=177\u201383 }}\n* {{Cite journal |first=Catherine |last=Edwards |title=The Millbank Penitentiary: excavations at the Tate Gallery (now Tate Britain), City of Westminster |journal=Transactions of the London and Middlesex Archaeological Society |volume=61 |year=2010 |pages=157\u201374 }}\n* {{cite book |last=Evans |first=Robin |title=The Fabrication of Virtue: English prison architecture, 1750\u20131840 |place=Cambridge |publisher=Cambridge University Press |year=1982 |isbn=0521239559 |pages=244\u2013250 }}\n* {{Cite book |first=Arthur |last=Griffiths |title=Memorials of Millbank and Chapters in Prison History |edition=2nd |place=London |publisher=Chapman & Hall |year=1884 |origyear=1875 |url=https://archive.org/details/memorialsofmillb00grif }}\n* {{Cite book |first=George Peter |last=Holford |title=An Account of the General Penitentiary at Millbank |place=London |year=1828 }}\n* {{Cite book |first1=Henry |last1=Mayhew |authorlink1=Henry Mayhew |first2=John |last2=Binny |title=The Criminal Prisons of London and Scenes of Prison Life |place=London |year=1862 }} (Chapter 5).\n* ''[[The Nuttall Encyclopaedia]]'', \"Millbank Prison\".\n* {{Cite book |first=Simon |last=Thurley |authorlink=Simon Thurley |title=Lost Buildings of Britain |place=London |publisher=Viking |year=2004 |ISBN=0-670-91521-1 }}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.victorianlondon.org/prisons/millbankprison.htm Collection of Victorian references]\n*[http://www.ph.ucla.edu/epi/snow/1859map/map1859_m-r_13-18.html 1859 map] - the penitentiary is the distinctive six-pointed building near the bottom\n*[http://www.millbank-emo.co.uk/ Millbank Estate today]\n\n{{coord|51|29|29|N|0|07|44|W|region:GB_type:landmark|display=title}}\n\n{{Prisons in London}}\n\n[[Category:1816 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:Defunct prisons in London]]\n[[Category:Former buildings and structures in the City of Westminster]]\n[[Category:Demolished buildings and structures in London]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures demolished in 1903]]\n[[Category:19th century in London]]\n[[Category:1890 disestablishments in England]]\n[[Category:Millbank]]\n[[Category:Demolished prisons]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Millbank Thomas Hosmer Shepherd pub 1829.jpg|thumb|upright=1.4|Millbank Prison in the 1820s]]\n'''Millbank Prison''' was a prison in [[Millbank]], [[Westminster]], [[London]], originally constructed as the National Penitentiary, and which for part of its history served as a holding facility for convicted prisoners before they were [[Penal transportation|transported to Australia]]. It was opened in 1816 and closed in 1890.\n\n==Construction==\n[[File:Millbank Prison Plan.jpg|thumb|right|upright=1.2|Plan of Millbank Prison]]\nThe site at Millbank was originally purchased in 1799 from the [[James Cecil, 1st Marquess of Salisbury|Marquess of Salisbury]] for \u00a312,000 by the philosopher [[Jeremy Bentham]], acting on behalf of [[the Crown]], for the erection of his proposed [[Panopticon]] prison as Britain's new National Penitentiary.<ref name=Timbs>{{cite book|first=John|last=Timbs |author-link=John Timbs|title=Curiosities of London: Exhibiting the Most Rare and Remarkable Objects of Interest in the Metropolis|url=https://archive.org/stream/curiositiesoflon00timbrich#page/697/mode/1up|year=1855|publisher=D. Bogue|page=697}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Semple |first=Janet |year=1993 |title=Bentham's Prison: a Study of the Panopticon Penitentiary |place=Oxford |publisher=Clarendon Press |isbn=0-19827387-8 |pages=218\u201322 }}</ref> After various changes in circumstance, the Panopticon plan was abandoned in 1812. Proposals for the National Penitentiary continued, however, and were given a legislative basis in the [[Penitentiary House, etc. Act 1812|Penitentiary House, etc. Act]] of 1812 (52 Geo. 3 c. 44). An architectural competition for a new prison building on the Millbank site attracted 43 entrants: the winning design was that of William Williams, drawing master at the [[Royal Military College, Sandhurst]]. Williams' basic plan was adapted by a practising architect, [[Thomas Hardwick]], who began construction in the same year. Hardwick resigned in 1813, and John Harvey took over the role. Harvey was dismissed in turn in 1815, and replaced by [[Robert Smirke (architect)|Robert Smirke]], who brought the project to completion in 1821.<ref name=\"handbook\">{{cite book |last=Cunningham |first=Peter |authorlink=Peter Cunningham (British writer) |chapter=Millbank Prison |title=Hand-book of London: past and present |edition=2nd |location=London |publisher=John Murray |year=1850 |pages=[https://archive.org/details/handbookoflondon00cunn/page/337 337]\u201338 |url=https://archive.org/details/handbookoflondon00cunn }}</ref> Further legislation was passed in the form of the [[Millbank Penitentiary Act 1816|Millbank Penitentiary Act]] of 1816 (56 Geo. 3 c. 63).\n\nThe marshy site on which the prison stood meant that the builders experienced problems of [[Groundwater-related subsidence|subsidence]] from the outset, and explains the succession of architects. Smirke finally resolved the difficulty by introducing a highly innovative [[concrete]] [[Floating raft system|raft]] to provide a secure foundation. However, this added considerably to the construction costs, which eventually totalled \u00a3500,000, more than twice the original estimate and equivalent to \u00a3500 per cell.<ref name=Timbs />\n\n==History==\nThe first prisoners, all women, were admitted on 26 June 1816. The first men arrived in January 1817. The prison held 103 men and 109 women by the end of 1817, and 452 men and 326 women by late 1822. Sentences of five to ten years in the National Penitentiary were offered as an alternative to [[Penal transportation|transportation]] to those thought most likely to reform. \n\nIn addition to the problems of construction, the marshy site fostered disease, to which the prisoners had little immunity owing to their extremely poor diet. In 1818 the authorities engaged Dr [[Alexander Copland Hutchison]] of Westminster Dispensary as Medical Supervisor, to oversee the health of the inmates.<ref>''Parliamentary Papers 1780\u20131849'', vol. 5, 1825: \"The General Penitentiary at Millbank\".</ref> In 1822&ndash;23 an epidemic swept through the prison, which seems to have comprised a mixture of [[dysentery]], [[scurvy]], [[Depression (mood)|depression]] and other disorders.<ref>Evans 1982, p. 249.</ref> The decision was eventually taken to evacuate the buildings for several months: the female prisoners were released, and the male prisoners temporarily transferred to the [[List of British prison hulks|prison hulks]] at [[Woolwich]], where their health improved.\n\nThe design of Millbank also turned out to be unsatisfactory. The network of corridors was so labyrinthine that even the warders got lost;<ref>Griffiths 1884, p. 27.</ref> and the ventilation system allowed sound to carry, so that prisoners could communicate between cells. The annual running costs turned out to be an unsupportable \u00a316,000.\n\nIn view of these problems, the decision was eventually taken to build a new \"model prison\" at [[Pentonville (HM Prison)|Pentonville]], which opened in 1842 and took over Millbank's role as the National Penitentiary. By an Act of Parliament of 1843, Millbank's status was downgraded, and it became a holding depot for convicts prior to [[Penal transportation|transportation]]. Every person sentenced to transportation was sent to Millbank first, where they were held for three months before their final destination was decided. By 1850, around 4,000 people were condemned annually to transportation from the UK.<ref name=\"handbook\"/> Prisoners awaiting transportation were kept in solitary confinement and restricted to silence for the first half of their sentence.\n\nLarge-scale transportation ended in 1853 (although the practice continued on a reduced scale until 1867); and Millbank then became an ordinary local prison, and from 1870 a military prison. By 1886 it had ceased to hold inmates, and it closed in 1890.<ref>Brodie ''et al.'' 2002, p. 60.</ref> Demolition began in 1892, and continued sporadically until 1903.\n\n==Description==\n[[File:Burial ground at Millbank Prison.JPG|thumb|The prison's burial ground, with the [[Houses of Parliament]] in the background. The image was published in 1862.]]\n[[File:Millbank Cassell's large-scale map of London c 1867.jpg|thumb|Map of 1867, showing the prison and its surroundings]]\nThe plan of the prison comprised a circular chapel at the centre of the site, surrounded by a three-storey hexagon made up of the governor's quarters, administrative offices and laundries, surrounded in turn by six pentagons of cell blocks. The buildings of each pentagon were set around a cluster of five small courtyards (with a [[watchtower]] at the centre) used as airing-yards, and in which prisoners undertook labour.<ref>Griffiths 1884, p. 26.</ref> The three outer angles of each pentagon were distinguished by tall circular towers, described in 1862 as \"[[Martello tower|Martello]]-like\": these served in part as watchtowers, but their primary purpose was to contain staircases and [[Flush toilet|water-closets]].<ref name=MayhewBinny>Mayhew and Binny 1862.</ref><ref>Holford 1828, plan of prison.</ref> The third and fourth pentagons (those to the north-west, furthest from the entrance) were used to house female prisoners, and the remaining four for male prisoners.\n\nIn the ''Handbook of London'' in 1850 the prison was described as follows:<ref name=\"handbook\"/>\n{{quote|A mass of brickwork equal to a fortress, on the left bank of the [[Thames]], close to [[Vauxhall Bridge]]; erected on ground bought in 1799 of the Marquis of Salisbury, and established pursuant to [[Penitentiary House, etc. Act 1812|52 Geo. III., c. 44]], passed Aug 20th, 1812. It was designed by Jeremy Bentham [factually incorrect], to whom the fee-simple of the ground was conveyed, and is said to have cost the enormous sum of half a million sterling. The external walls form an irregular octagon, and enclose upwards of sixteen acres of land. Its ground-plan resembles a wheel, the governor's house occupying a circle in the centre, from which radiate six piles of building, terminating externally in towers. The ground on which it stands is raised but little above the river, and was at one time considered unhealthy. It was first named \"The Penitentiary\", or \"Penitentiary House for London and Middlesex\", and was called \"The Millbank Prison\" pursuant to [[Millbank Prison Act 1843|6 & 7 of Victoria, c. 26]]. It is the largest prison in London. Every male and female convict sentenced to [[Penal transportation|transportation]] in Great Britain is sent to Millbank previous to the sentence being executed. Here they remain about three months under the close inspection of the three inspectors of the prison, at the end of which time the inspectors report to the Home Secretary, and recommend the place of transportation. The number of persons in Great Britain and Ireland condemned to transportation every year amounts to about 4000. So far as the accommodation of the prison permits, the [[separate system]] is adopted.}}\n\nEach cell had a single window (looking into the pentagon courtyard), and was equipped with a washing tub, a wooden stool, a hammock and bedding, and books including a Bible, a prayer-book, a hymn-book, an arithmetic-book, a work entitled ''Home and Common Things'', and publications of the [[Society for Promoting Christian Knowledge]].<ref name=MayhewBinny/>\n\n[[Irish republicanism|Irish republican]] prisoner [[Michael Davitt]], who was held briefly at Millbank in 1870, described the experience: \n\n{{quote|[[Big Ben|Westminster Clock]] is not far distant from the penitentiary, so that its every stroke is as distinctly heard in each cell as if it were situated in one of the prison yards. At each quarter of an hour, day and night it chimes a bar of the \"[[Old 100th|Old Hundredth]]\" and those solemn tones strike on the ears of the lonely listeners like the voice of some monster spirit singing the funeral dirge of Time.<ref>{{cite book |title=Irish political prisoners: speeches of John O'Connor Power in the House of Commons on the subject of amnesty, &c., and a statement by Mr. Michael Davitt on prison treatment |first1=John O'Connor |last1=Power |first2=Michael |last2=Davitt |place=London |year=1878 |page=52 }}</ref>}}\n\n==Later development of the site==\n[[File:OS Millbank Tate etc 2.jpg|thumb|The site of the prison in 1916, after redevelopment. Its outline is still visible in the pattern of streets and buildings.]]\nAs the prison was progressively demolished its site was redeveloped. The principal new buildings erected were the National Gallery of British Art (now [[Tate Britain]]), which opened in 1897; the [[Royal Army Medical School]], the buildings of which were adapted in 2005 to become the [[Chelsea College of Art & Design]]; and{{spaced ndash}}using the original bricks of the prison{{spaced ndash}}the [[Millbank#Notable buildings|Millbank Estate]], a housing estate built by the [[London County Council]] (LCC) between 1897 and 1902. The estate comprises 17 buildings, each named after a distinguished painter, and is [[Listed building#England and Wales|Grade II listed]].\n\n==Surviving remains==\n[[File:Pimlico buttress 1.jpg|thumb|upright|left|Surviving [[bollard]]]]\n[[File:Millbank Prison Ditch.jpg|thumb|Surviving perimeter ditch]]\n\nA large circular [[bollard]] stands by the river with the inscription: \"Near this site stood Millbank Prison which was opened in 1816 and closed in 1890. This buttress stood at the head of the river steps from which, until 1867, prisoners sentenced to transportation embarked on their journey to Australia.\"\n\nPart of the perimeter ditch of the prison survives running between Cureton Street and John Islip Street. It is now used as a clothes-drying area for residents of Wilkie House.\n\nArchaeological investigations in the late 1990s and early 2000s on the sites of Chelsea College of Art and Design and Tate Britain recorded significant remains of the foundations of the external pentagon walls of the prison, of parts of the inner hexagon, of two of the courtyard watchtowers, of drainage [[culvert]]s, and of Smirke's concrete raft.<ref>Edwards 2007.</ref><ref>Edwards 2010.</ref>\n\nThe granite gate piers at the entrance of Purbeck House, High Street, [[Swanage]] in Dorset, and a granite bollard next to the gate, are thought by [[English Heritage]] to be possibly from Millbank Prison.<ref>{{NHLE|num=1119904 |desc=Gate piers and bollard at entrance to Purbeck House, High Street|grade=II|accessdate=24 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Cultural references==\n[[Charles Dickens]] describes the prison in chapter 52 (\"Obstinacy\") of his novel, ''[[Bleak House]]'' (1852\u20133). One of the characters is put into custody there, and other characters go to visit him. Esther Summerson, one of the book's narrators, gives a brief description of its layout.<ref>{{cite book |first=Charles |last=Dickens |authorlink=Charles Dickens |title=Bleak House |location=London |publisher=Chapman & Hall |date=1853 |page=563 |url=https://archive.org/stream/bleakhouse00dickiala#page/562/mode/2up }}</ref>\n\nIn [[Henry James]]'s [[Literary realism|realist]] novel ''[[The Princess Casamassima]]'' (1886) the prison is the \"primal scene\" of Hyacinth Robinson's life: the visit to his mother, dying in the infirmary, is described in chapter 3. James visited Millbank on 12 December 1884 to gain material.<ref>''Henry James letters'', edited by Leon Edel, Vol. 3: 1883\u20131895, Cambridge, Mass.: Belknap Press of Harvard University Press; London: Macmillan, 1980, page 61.</ref> \n\nSir [[Arthur Conan Doyle]] in chapter 8 of ''[[The Sign of the Four|The Sign of Four]]'' (1890) refers to [[Sherlock Holmes|Holmes]] and [[Dr. Watson|Watson]] crossing the Thames from the house of Mordecai Smith and landing by the Millbank Penitentiary.\n\nIn chapter 8 of Conan Doyle's ''[[The Lost World (Conan Doyle novel)|The Lost World]]'' (1912), [[Professor Challenger]] says that he dislikes walking along the Thames as it is always sad to see one's final destination. Challenger means that he expects to be buried at [[Westminster Abbey]], but his rival Professor Summerlee responds sardonically that he understands that Millbank Prison has been demolished.\n\nThe prison is a key location within [[Sarah Waters]]' novel ''[[Affinity (novel)|Affinity]]'' (1999).\n\nThe prison, Bentham's philosophy surrounding it, and a fictionalized account of Smirke's role in its construction play a key part in the plot of horror fiction podcast [[The Magnus Archives]] by Jonathan Sims.<ref>{{cite podcast|url=http://rustyquill.com/the-magnus-archives/|title=Panopticon|website=The Magnus Archives|publisher=|host=|date=17 October 2020|time=|access-date=14 April 2020|last=|first=}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n*[[List of demolished buildings and structures in London]]\n*[[Convicts in Australia]]\n*[[Penal transportation]]\n*[[Separate system]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{Cite book |first1=Allan |last1=Brodie |first2=Jane |last2=Croom |first3=James O. |last3=Davies |title=English Prisons: an architectural history |place =Swindon |publisher=English Heritage |year=2002 |ISBN=1-873592-53-1 |url=http://archaeologydataservice.ac.uk/archives/view/eh_monographs_2014/contents.cfm?mono=1089057}}\n* {{Cite journal |first=Catherine |last=Edwards |title=The Millbank Penitentiary: excavations at the Chelsea School of Art and Design |journal=London Archaeologist |volume=11.7 |year=2007 |pages=177\u201383 }}\n* {{Cite journal |first=Catherine |last=Edwards |title=The Millbank Penitentiary: excavations at the Tate Gallery (now Tate Britain), City of Westminster |journal=Transactions of the London and Middlesex Archaeological Society |volume=61 |year=2010 |pages=157\u201374 }}\n* {{cite book |last=Evans |first=Robin |title=The Fabrication of Virtue: English prison architecture, 1750\u20131840 |place=Cambridge |publisher=Cambridge University Press |year=1982 |isbn=0521239559 |pages=244\u2013250 }}\n* {{Cite book |first=Arthur |last=Griffiths |title=Memorials of Millbank and Chapters in Prison History |edition=2nd |place=London |publisher=Chapman & Hall |year=1884 |origyear=1875 |url=https://archive.org/details/memorialsofmillb00grif }}\n* {{Cite book |first=George Peter |last=Holford |title=An Account of the General Penitentiary at Millbank |place=London |year=1828 }}\n* {{Cite book |first1=Henry |last1=Mayhew |authorlink1=Henry Mayhew |first2=John |last2=Binny |title=The Criminal Prisons of London and Scenes of Prison Life |place=London |year=1862 }} (Chapter 5).\n* ''[[The Nuttall Encyclopaedia]]'', \"Millbank Prison\".\n* {{Cite book |first=Simon |last=Thurley |authorlink=Simon Thurley |title=Lost Buildings of Britain |place=London |publisher=Viking |year=2004 |ISBN=0-670-91521-1 }}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.victorianlondon.org/prisons/millbankprison.htm Collection of Victorian references]\n*[http://www.ph.ucla.edu/epi/snow/1859map/map1859_m-r_13-18.html 1859 map] - the penitentiary is the distinctive six-pointed building near the bottom\n*[http://www.millbank-emo.co.uk/ Millbank Estate today]\n\n{{coord|51|29|29|N|0|07|44|W|region:GB_type:landmark|display=title}}\n\n{{Prisons in London}}\n\n[[Category:1816 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:Defunct prisons in London]]\n[[Category:Former buildings and structures in the City of Westminster]]\n[[Category:Demolished buildings and structures in London]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures demolished in 1903]]\n[[Category:19th century in London]]\n[[Category:1890 disestablishments in England]]\n[[Category:Millbank]]\n[[Category:Demolished prisons]]\n", "name_user": "Jessiehsu221", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixed a date in the citation for the sentence on The Magnus Archives under Cultural references.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Millbank_Prison"}
{"title_page": "Endau-Rompin National Park", "text_new": "{{Infobox protected area \n| name = Endau-Rompin National Park<br>Taman Negara Endau-Rompin\n| iucn_category = II\n| photo = Top of Janing Barat, Endau Rompin, Johor, Malaysia.jpg\n| photo_caption = View from the top of Janing Barat.\n| map = Malaysia\n| map_caption = \n| map_width = \n| label = '''Endau-Rompin'''\n| label_position = right\n| location = [[Johor]] and [[Pahang]], [[Peninsular Malaysia]]\n| nearest_city = [[Kahang]]\n| area_km2 = 870\n| established = 1993\n| visitation_num = \n| visitation_year = \n| governing_body = [[Johor Park Corporation]]\n}}\n\n'''Endau-Rompin National Park''' ([[Malay language|Malay]]: ''Taman Negara Endau-Rompin'') is a protected [[tropical rainforest]] in the southernmost prolongation of the [[Tenasserim Hills]], [[Malaysia]]. It is south of the state of [[Pahang]] and northeast of [[Johor]] covering an area of approximately {{convert|870|sqkm|abbr=on}}, making it the second-largest [[national park]] in [[Peninsular Malaysia]] after [[Taman Negara]]. It has approximately {{convert|26|km|abbr=on}} of trail. It is the second national park proclaimed by the government of Malaysia. [[Gunung Besar]], the second-highest peak in Johor, is in the park.\n\nThe park takes its name from the [[Endau River|Endau]] and [[Rompin River|Rompin]] rivers that flow through the park. Other rivers that flow through the park are the [[Segamat River|Segamat]], Selai, and Jasin.\n\nDuring the monsoon season from November till March, the park is closed to the public. Fishing is banned from September till October during mating season.\n\n==History==\n[[File:Mohd Hafiz Noor Shams, 2007.jpg|thumb|290px|Jasin River joins Endau at Kuala Jasin.]]\nThe first scientific study of the area was conducted in 1892 by H.W. Lake and Lieutenant H.J. Kelsall. With the aid of the study, the forest complex of [[Endau]]-[[Kluang]] was gazetted as a forest reserve in 1933. Later in 1972, the forest reserve was expanded to include [[Lesong]] forest reserve in Pahang.<ref name=\"JM\">Journey Malaysia. [http://www.journeymalaysia.com/MR_endau.htm Endau Rompin National Park]. Extracted April 24, 2007</ref>\n\nIn the same year, the federal government came up with a proposal to federally protect 2,000&nbsp;km\u00b2 of the complex as a national park. At that time there was no legal mechanism to create a national park. In 1980, the [[National Parks Act 1980 (Malaysia)]] was passed by the [[Malaysian Parliament]]. However, dispute between federal and state powers prevented the creation of a national park in the area at that time.<ref name=\"MNS\">Malaysian Nature Society. [http://www.mns.org.my/artabout.php?aid=20 Endau Rompin National Park] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928031818/http://www.mns.org.my/artabout.php?aid=20 |date=2007-09-28 }}. Extracted April 24, 2007</ref> Five years later, the [[Department of Wildlife and National Parks]] proposed roughly the same areas to be gazetted as wildlife sanctuary to protect the critically endangered Sumatran rhinoceros.<ref name=\"MNS\" />\n\n==Flora and fauna==\nEndau-Rompin is one of the oldest tropical rainforest complexes in the world and features rock formations some 248&nbsp;million years old. \n\nMammals endemic to Endau-Rompin include the [[Malayan tiger]], [[Indochinese leopard]], [[Clouded leopard]], [[Asian golden cat]], [[Leopard cat]], [[Marbled cat]], [[Asian elephant]], [[Malayan tapir]], [[Bornean bearded pig]], [[Banded pig]], [[Barking deer]], [[Sambar deer]],  [[lesser mouse deer]], [[greater mouse deer]], [[Sunbear]],  [[Long-tailed macaque]],[[Pig-tailed macaque]], [[Dusky leaf monkey]] and [[Banded Langur]].\n\nIt used to have the largest remaining population of the threatened [[Northern Sumatran rhinoceros]] species on the [[Malay Peninsula]], but they are now extinct in the wild for the whole of Malaysia.<ref>https://news.nationalgeographic.com/2015/09/150930-sumatran-rhino-extinction-indonesia-animals-conservation/</ref>\n\nThe Gollum's toad, ''[[Ingerophrynus gollum]]'', is only known from the Endau-Rompin National Park.<ref name=ARPM/><ref name=Frost/>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Belum-Temengor]]\n* [[List of national parks of Malaysia]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em|refs=\n<ref name=ARPM>{{cite web |url=http://www.amphibia.my/page.php?pageid=s_foundk&s_id=14&search1=Ingerophrynus%20gollum&species=Ingerophrynus%20gollum&submit=Search! |title=''Ingerophrynus gollum'' |work=Amphibians and Reptiles of Peninsular Malaysia |accessdate=8 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Frost>{{cite web |url=http://research.amnh.org/vz/herpetology/amphibia/index.php//Amphibia/Anura/Bufonidae/Ingerophrynus/Ingerophrynus-gollum |title=''Ingerophrynus gollum'' Grismer, 2007 |author=Frost, Darrel R. |year=2018 |work=Amphibian Species of the World: an Online Reference. Version 6.0 |publisher=American Museum of Natural History |accessdate=8 March 2018}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Endau-Rompin National Park}}\n* [https://www.johornationalparks.gov.my/v3/ \n* [https://www.facebook.com/TamanNegaraJohor/ \n* [http://www.tourism.gov.my/en/my/web-page/places/states-of-malaysia/johor/endau-rompin-national-park Tourism Malaysia - Endau Rompin National Park]\n* {{Wikivoyage-inline}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20140218033310/http://www.virtualmalaysia.com/endau-rompin-johor-national-park/ e-Tourism Portal] - Virtual Malaysia\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20140223121454/http://www.virtualmalaysia.com/endau-rompin-national-park-witness-the-power-and-majesty-of-natural-forces/ Travel Ideas] - Malaysia Social Travel Channel\n\n{{National parks of Malaysia}}\n{{East Coast Economic Region}}\n{{coord|2.438915|N|103.272858|E|name=Endau Rompin National Park|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:National parks of Malaysia]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Johor]]\n[[Category:Protected areas established in 1993]]\n[[Category:Geography of Johor]]\n[[Category:Geography of Pahang]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Pahang]]\n[[Category:1993 establishments in Malaysia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox protected area \n| name = Endau-Rompin National Park<br>Taman Negara Endau-Rompin\n| iucn_category = II\n| photo = Top of Janing Barat, Endau Rompin, Johor, Malaysia.jpg\n| photo_caption = View from the top of Janing Barat.\n| map = Malaysia\n| map_caption = \n| map_width = \n| label = '''Endau-Rompin'''\n| label_position = right\n| location = [[Johor]] and [[Pahang]], [[Peninsular Malaysia]]\n| nearest_city = [[Kahang]]\n| area_km2 = 870\n| established = 1993\n| visitation_num = \n| visitation_year = \n| governing_body = [[Johor Park Corporation]]\n}}\n\n'''Endau-Rompin National Park''' ([[Malay language|Malay]]: ''Taman Negara Endau-Rompin'') is a protected [[tropical rainforest]] in the southernmost prolongation of the [[Tenasserim Hills]], [[Malaysia]]. It is south of the state of [[Pahang]] and northeast of [[Johor]] covering an area of approximately {{convert|870|sqkm|abbr=on}}, making it the second-largest [[national park]] in [[Peninsular Malaysia]] after [[Taman Negara]]. It has approximately {{convert|26|km|abbr=on}} of trail. It is the second national park proclaimed by the government of Malaysia. [[Gunung Besar]], the second-highest peak in Johor, is in the park.\n\nThe park takes its name from the [[Endau River|Endau]] and [[Rompin River|Rompin]] rivers that flow through the park. Other rivers that flow through the park are the [[Segamat River|Segamat]], Selai, and Jasin.\n\nDuring the monsoon season from November till March, the park is closed to the public. Fishing is banned from September till October during mating season.\n\n==History==\n[[File:Mohd Hafiz Noor Shams, 2007.jpg|thumb|290px|Jasin River joins Endau at Kuala Jasin.]]\nThe first scientific study of the area was conducted in 1892 by H.W. Lake and Lieutenant H.J. Kelsall. With the aid of the study, the forest complex of [[Endau]]-[[Kluang]] was gazetted as a forest reserve in 1933. Later in 1972, the forest reserve was expanded to include [[Lesong]] forest reserve in Pahang.<ref name=\"JM\">Journey Malaysia. [http://www.journeymalaysia.com/MR_endau.htm Endau Rompin National Park]. Extracted April 24, 2007</ref>\n\nIn the same year, the federal government came up with a proposal to federally protect 2,000&nbsp;km\u00b2 of the complex as a national park. At that time there was no legal mechanism to create a national park. In 1980, the [[National Parks Act 1980 (Malaysia)]] was passed by the [[Malaysian Parliament]]. However, dispute between federal and state powers prevented the creation of a national park in the area at that time.<ref name=\"MNS\">Malaysian Nature Society. [http://www.mns.org.my/artabout.php?aid=20 Endau Rompin National Park] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928031818/http://www.mns.org.my/artabout.php?aid=20 |date=2007-09-28 }}. Extracted April 24, 2007</ref> Five years later, the [[Department of Wildlife and National Parks]] proposed roughly the same areas to be gazetted as wildlife sanctuary to protect the critically endangered Sumatran rhinoceros.<ref name=\"MNS\" />\n\n==Flora and fauna==\nEndau-Rompin is one of the oldest tropical rainforest complexes in the world and features rock formations some 248&nbsp;million years old. Mammals endemic to Endau-Rompin include the [[Malayan tiger]], [[Indochinese leopard]], [[Clouded leopard]], [[Asian golden cat]], [[Leopard cat]], [[Marbled cat]], [[Asian elephant]], [[Malayan tapir]], [[Bornean bearded pig]], [[Banded pig]], [[Barking deer]], [[Sambar deer]],  [[lesser mouse deer]], [[greater mouse deer]], [[sunbear]],  [[Long-tailed macaque]],[[Pig-tailed macaque]], [[Dusky Langur]] and [[ Banded Langur]].\n\nIt used to have the largest remaining population of the threatened [[Northern Sumatran rhinoceros]] species on the [[Malay Peninsula]], but they are now extinct in the wild for the whole of Malaysia.<ref>https://news.nationalgeographic.com/2015/09/150930-sumatran-rhino-extinction-indonesia-animals-conservation/</ref>\n\nThe Gollum's toad, ''[[Ingerophrynus gollum]]'', is only known from the Endau-Rompin National Park.<ref name=ARPM/><ref name=Frost/>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Belum-Temengor]]\n* [[List of national parks of Malaysia]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em|refs=\n<ref name=ARPM>{{cite web |url=http://www.amphibia.my/page.php?pageid=s_foundk&s_id=14&search1=Ingerophrynus%20gollum&species=Ingerophrynus%20gollum&submit=Search! |title=''Ingerophrynus gollum'' |work=Amphibians and Reptiles of Peninsular Malaysia |accessdate=8 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Frost>{{cite web |url=http://research.amnh.org/vz/herpetology/amphibia/index.php//Amphibia/Anura/Bufonidae/Ingerophrynus/Ingerophrynus-gollum |title=''Ingerophrynus gollum'' Grismer, 2007 |author=Frost, Darrel R. |year=2018 |work=Amphibian Species of the World: an Online Reference. Version 6.0 |publisher=American Museum of Natural History |accessdate=8 March 2018}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Endau-Rompin National Park}}\n* [https://www.johornationalparks.gov.my/v3/ \n* [https://www.facebook.com/TamanNegaraJohor/ \n* [http://www.tourism.gov.my/en/my/web-page/places/states-of-malaysia/johor/endau-rompin-national-park Tourism Malaysia - Endau Rompin National Park]\n* {{Wikivoyage-inline}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20140218033310/http://www.virtualmalaysia.com/endau-rompin-johor-national-park/ e-Tourism Portal] - Virtual Malaysia\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20140223121454/http://www.virtualmalaysia.com/endau-rompin-national-park-witness-the-power-and-majesty-of-natural-forces/ Travel Ideas] - Malaysia Social Travel Channel\n\n{{National parks of Malaysia}}\n{{East Coast Economic Region}}\n{{coord|2.438915|N|103.272858|E|name=Endau Rompin National Park|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:National parks of Malaysia]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Johor]]\n[[Category:Protected areas established in 1993]]\n[[Category:Geography of Johor]]\n[[Category:Geography of Pahang]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Pahang]]\n[[Category:1993 establishments in Malaysia]]\n", "name_user": "SteveGorilla", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eFlora and fauna", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Endau-Rompin_National_Park"}
{"title_page": "All My Heroes Are Dead (R.A. the Rugged Man album)", "text_new": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = All My Heroes Are Dead\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[R.A. the Rugged Man]]\n| cover      = AMHAD cover.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = April 17, 2020\n| recorded   = 2017-2020\n| venue      = \n| studio     = [[Chris Conway (recording engineer)|No Mystery Studio]], New York City\n| genre      = [[Hip hop music|Hip hop]]\n| length     = 1:15:51\n| label      = [[Nature Sounds]]\n| producer   = [[Prince Paul (producer)|Prince Paul]], [[DJ Jazzy Jeff]], [[Psycho Les]], [[Mr. Green (record producer)|Mr. Green]], [[Classified (rapper)|Classified]], Teddy Roxspin, Shroom<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ratheruggedman.net/products/all-my-heroes-are-dead-heroes-edition |title=R.A. The Rugged Man All My Heroes Are Dead Deluxe Edition |publisher=R.A. Thorburn |date=2020-04-04 |accessdate=2020-04-04}}</ref>\n| prev_title = [[Legends Never Die (R.A. the Rugged Man album)|Legends Never Die]]\n| prev_year  = 2013\n| next_title = \n| next_year  = \n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = All My Heroes Are Dead\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = Legendary Loser\n | single1date = January 15, 2020\n | single2     = Wondering (How to Believe)\n | single2date = March 11, 2020\n}}\n}}\n\n'''''All My Heroes Are Dead''''' is the third [[studio album]] from [[New York City]] hip hop artist [[R.A. the Rugged Man]]. The album is scheduled to be released on April 17, 2020, by [[Nature Sounds]]. It is the follow up to 2013's ''[[Legends Never Die (R.A. the Rugged Man album)|Legends Never Die]]''. The album features [[guest appearance]]s from [[Ghostface Killah]], [[Inspectah Deck]], [[Kool G Rap]], [[Ice-T]], [[Chuck D]], [[Timbo King]], [[Atmosphere]], [[Vinnie Paz]], [[Eamon (singer)|Eamon]], [[Brand Nubian]] among others.<ref>{{cite web|last=Julian |first=Can |url=http://www.rap-n-blues.com/r-a-the-rugged-man-legends-never-die-artwork-tracklist/ |title=R.A. the Rugged Man - Legends Never Die (Artwork & Tracklist) |publisher=Rap-n-blues.com |date=2013-08-13 |accessdate=2013-09-16}}</ref> The album's production was handled by [[Prince Paul (producer)|Prince Paul]], [[Psycho Les]], [[Mr. Green (record producer)|Mr. Green]] and [[Classified (rapper)|Classified]] among others.\n\n==Background==\nFollowing the success of ''Legends Never Die'', R.A. the Rugged Man announced he would begin working on a follow up project. The first single from the album, \"Legendary Loser\", produced by Psycho Les of The Beatnuts, was released on January 15, 2020 alongside visuals and confirmation of the project title.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ambrosiaforheads.com/2020/01/ra-the-rugged-man-loser-video/ |title=R.A. The Rugged Man Is A Hip-Hop Showman Who Rapped His Way From Loser To Legend |publisher=Ambrosia4Heads |date=2020-01-16 |accessdate=2020-04-04}}</ref> On April 13, 2020 an official trailer was released for the album. The visual promotion, produced by Thorburn, was created as a homage to various [[B-Movie]] action films of the 1980s, as well as Thorburn's own [[Bad Biology]]. \n\n==Track listing==\n{{tracklist\n| extra_column    = Producer(s)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://hiphopdx.com/news/id.55127/title.r-a-the-rugged-man-unveils-all-my-heroes-are-dead-tracklist-drops-golden-oldies-with-slug |title=R.A. The Rugged Man Unveils 'All My Heroes Are Dead' Tracklist & Drops 'Golden Oldies' With Slug |publisher=HipHopDX.com |date=2020-03-26 |accessdate=2020-04-04}}</ref><ref>https://twitter.com/RAtheRuggedMan/status/1249719024340078593</ref>\n| title1          = All My Heroes Are Dead (The Introduction)\n| note1           = \n| extra1          = \n| length1         = 2:33\n| title2          = Legendary Loser\n| extra2          = [[Psycho Les]]\n| length2         = 4:21\n| title3          = Golden Oldies\n| note3           = featuring [[Atmosphere (music group)|Atmosphere]] and [[Eamon (singer)|Eamon]]\n| extra3          = [[The Kickdrums]]\n| 