{"title_page": "1913\u201314 Toronto Hockey Club season", "text_new": "{{Infobox IcehockeyTeamSeason\n  |Season=1913\u201314\n  |year=1913\n  |Team=Toronto Hockey Club\n  |League=NHA\n  |Conference=\n  |ConferenceRank=\n  |Division=\n  |DivisionRank=\n  |Record=13\u20137\u20130\n  |HomeRecord=8\u20132\u20130\n  |RoadRecord=5\u20135\u20130\n  |GoalsFor=93\n  |GoalsAgainst=65\n  |GeneralManager=[[Percy Quinn]]\n  |Coach=[[Jack Marshall (ice hockey)|Jack Marshall]]\n  |Captain=[[Scotty Davidson]]\n  |AltCaptain=\n  |Arena=[[Mutual Street Arena|Arena Gardens]]\n  |Attendance=\n  |GoalsLeader=\n  |AssistsLeader=\n  |PointsLeader=\n  |PlusMinusLeader=\n  |PIMLeader=\n  |WinsLeader=\n  |GAALeader=\n  |StanleyCup=Yes\n}}\n\nThe '''[[1913\u201314 NHA season|1913\u201314]] [[Toronto Blueshirts|Toronto Hockey Club]] season''' was the second season of the Toronto franchise in the [[National Hockey Association]] (NHA). The Blue Shirts would win the NHA championship in a playoff to take over the [[Stanley Cup]]. The club then played and defeated the [[Victoria Aristocrats]] in the first hockey \"World Series\" against the champion of the [[Pacific Coast Hockey Association]] (PCHA).\n\n==Off-season==\nBruce Ridpath resigned as general manager of the club prior to the season, replaced by Jack Marshall. Ridpath himself tried out as a player but gave up his comeback before the season started. Of the previous season's squad, [[Archie McLean (ice hockey)|Archie McLean]] was dropped and [[Frank Nighbor]] moved to British Columbia. [[Jack Walker (ice hockey)|Jack Walker]], who had played one game with Toronto in the previous season before playing in the Maritime league was added. [[Con Corbeau]] was acquired from the [[Toronto Ontarios]] just before the start of the season.{{sfn|Harper|2013|pp=248\u2013249}}\n\n==Regular season==\n[[File:Torontos.jpg|thumb|right|250px|The 1913\u201314 Torontos]]\nHarry Cameron suffered a separated shoulder and the Torontos acquired [[George McNamara]] from the Ontarios for cash in mid-season. The Torontos had a two-game lead in the standings with two games to go, but lost both to drop into a tie with the Montreal Canadiens. It was rumoured that the Torontos had thrown the last two games to get an extra home game from a final with Montreal.{{sfn|Harper|2013|pp=251\u2013252}}\n\n===Final standings===\n{{1913\u201314 NHA standings |team=BLU}}\n\n===Schedule and results===\n{|class=\"wikitable\" width=\"70%\"\n|- align=\"center\"  bgcolor=\"#dddddd\"\n| '''#''' || '''Date''' || '''Visitor''' || '''Score''' || '''Home''' || '''Record''' || '''Pts'''\n|- align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#bbffbb\"\n| 1 || December 27 || [[Montreal Canadiens]] || 0\u20133 || Toronto || 1\u20130\u20130 || 2\n|- align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#ffbbbb\"\n| 2 || December 30 || Toronto || 3\u20137 || [[Montreal Wanderers]] || 1\u20131\u20130 || 2\n|- align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#bbffbb\"\n| 3 || January 3 || [[Quebec Bulldogs]] || 3\u20136 || Toronto || 2\u20131\u20130 || 4\n|- align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#bbffbb\"\n| 4 || January 7 || Toronto || 9\u20133 || [[Toronto Ontarios]] || 3\u20131\u20130 || 6\n|- align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#ffbbbb\"\n| 5 || January 10 || [[Ottawa Senators (original)|Ottawa Senators]] || 3\u20132 || Toronto || 3\u20132\u20130 || 6\n|- align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#bbffbb\"\n| 6 || January 14 || [[Montreal Wanderers]] || 2\u201310 || Toronto || 4\u20132\u20130 || 8\n|- align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#bbffbb\"\n| 7 || January 17 || Toronto || 9\u20134 || [[Quebec Bulldogs]] || 5\u20132\u20130 || 10\n|- align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#bbffbb\"\n| 8 || January 21 || [[Toronto Ontarios]] || 2\u20139 || Toronto || 6\u20132\u20130 || 12\n|- align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#ffbbbb\"\n| 9 || January 24 || Toronto || 1\u20134 || [[Ottawa Senators (original)|Ottawa Senators]]|| 6\u20133\u20130 || 12\n|- align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#ffbbbb\"\n| 10 || January 28 || Toronto || 3\u20134 || [[Montreal Canadiens]] || 6\u20134\u20130 || 12\n|- align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#bbffbb\"\n| 11 || January 31 || Toronto || 5\u20133 || [[Montreal Wanderers]] || 7\u20134\u20130 || 14\n|- align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#bbffbb\"\n| 12 || February 4 || [[Ottawa Senators (original)|Ottawa Senators]] || 1\u20132 || Toronto || 8\u20134\u20130 || 16\n|- align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#ffbbbb\"\n| 13 || February 7 || Toronto || 3\u20139 || [[Montreal Canadiens]] || 8\u20135\u20130 || 16\n|- align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#bbffbb\"\n| 14 || February 11 || [[Quebec Bulldogs]] || 3\u20134 || Toronto || 9\u20135\u20130 || 18\n|- align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#bbffbb\"\n| 15 || February 14 || [[Toronto Ontarios]] || 1\u20133 || Toronto || 10\u20135\u20130 || 20\n|- align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#bbffbb\"\n| 16 || February 18 || Toronto || 4\u20131 || [[Ottawa Senators (original)|Ottawa Senators]]|| 11\u20135\u20130 || 22\n|- align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#bbffbb\"\n| 17 || February 21 || [[Montreal Canadiens]] || 2\u20133 || Toronto || 12\u20135\u20130 || 24\n|- align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#bbffbb\"\n| 18 || February 25 || Toronto || 6\u20131 || [[Toronto Ontarios]] || 13\u20135\u20130 || 26\n|- align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#ffbbbb\"\n| 19 || February 28 || Toronto || 3\u20135 || [[Quebec Bulldogs]] || 13\u20136\u20130 || 26\n|- align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#ffbbbb\"\n| 20 || March 4 || [[Montreal Wanderers]] || 7\u20135 || Toronto || 13\u20137\u20130 || 26\n|}\n<ref name=\"coleman\">{{cite book |last=Coleman|first=Charles|title=The Trail of the Stanley Cup, Vol. 1, 1893\u20131926 inc.|year=1966|publisher=NHL}}</ref>\n\n==NHA playoffs==\nTied at the top of the standings, the Blueshirts and Canadiens faced off in a two-game, total goals series for the league championship and [[Stanley Cup]]. The Blueshirts won the series 6\u20132.\n\n;Toronto 6, Montreal Canadiens 2\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\" width=\"70%\"\n|- align=\"center\"  bgcolor=\"#dddddd\"\n| '''#''' || '''Date''' || '''Visitor''' || '''Score''' || '''Home''' || '''Record'''\n|- align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#ffbbbb\"\n| 1 || March 7 || Toronto || 0\u20132 || [[Montreal Canadiens]] || 0\u20131\n|- align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#bbffbb\"\n| 2 || March 11 || [[Montreal Canadiens]] || 0\u20136 || Toronto || 1\u20131\n|}\n<ref name=\"coleman\" />\n\n==Stanley Cup playoffs==\nThe 1913\u201314 season marked the end of the challenge era in [[Stanley Cup]] history. After dispatching the Canadiens, the Blueshirts faced off against the [[Victoria Aristocrats]] of the [[Pacific Coast Hockey Association]] (PCHA) in a best-of-five series, with all games played at the [[Arena Gardens]]. As one of the duties of the hockey commission for the NHA, PCHA and Maritime leagues, the playoff with the PCHA had been arranged prior to the season, but it had not been cleared with the Stanley Cup trustees.  A controversy erupted when a letter arrived from the Stanley Cup trustees on March 17, that the trustees would not let the Stanley Cup travel west, as they did not consider Victoria a proper challenger because they had not formally notified the trustees.<ref>{{cite news\n |work=Saskatoon Phoenix |title=Stanley Cup Contest May Not Be for the Mug, After All is Said |date=March 18, 1914 |page=8}}</ref> However, on March 18, Trustee William Foran stated that it was a misunderstanding. PCHA president Frank Patrick had not filed a challenge, because he had expected Emmett Quinn of the NHA to make all of the arrangements in his role as hockey commissioner, whereas the trustees thought they were being deliberately ignored. In any case, all arrangements had been ironed out and the Victoria challenge was accepted.<ref>{{cite news |work=Montreal Daily Mail |date=March 19, 1914 |title=A Tempest In a Teapot |page=9}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |work=Toronto Globe and Mail |title=Stanley Cup Muddle Cleared Up |date=March 19, 1914 |page=}}</ref> The trustees later sent a letter to league executives that Stanley Cup playoff arrangements would be handled by the leagues themselves henceforth.\n\nTotal attendance for the series was 14,260, out of a possible 22,500 (including standing room) capacity at the Arena. At the time, professional hockey was less of a draw than [[Ontario Hockey Association]] (OHA) senior hockey. Two games between local OHA senior teams had drawn over 14,000.<ref>{{cite news |work=Toronto Globe |date=March 21, 1914 |title=Puckerings |page=22}}</ref> The Torontos players and staff received $297 each as their share of the gate receipts.<ref>{{cite news |work=Toronto Globe |date=March 21, 1914 |title=Toronto Players Receive $297 Each |page=22}}</ref>\n\n;Toronto 3, Victoria 0\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\" width=\"70%\"\n|- align=\"center\"  bgcolor=\"#dddddd\"\n| '''#''' || '''Date''' || '''Visitor''' || '''Score''' || '''Home''' || '''Record'''\n|- align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#bbffbb\"\n| 1 || March 14 || [[Victoria Aristocrats]] || 2\u20135 || Toronto || 1\u20130\n|- align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#bbffbb\"\n| 2 || March 17 || [[Victoria Aristocrats]] || 5\u20136 || Toronto || 2\u20130\n|- align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#bbffbb\"\n| 3 || March 19 || [[Victoria Aristocrats]] || 1\u20132 || Toronto || 3\u20130\n|}\n<ref name=\"coleman\" />\n\n==Toronto Hockey Club 1914 Stanley Cup Champions==\n[[File:1914_Toronto_Hockey_Club_Worlds_Champions_Medal.jpg|thumb|right|<center> 1914 Worlds Champions Medal <br> Issued to Claude Wilson</center>]]\nWhen the Stanley Cup arrived in Toronto, it was put on public display in the window of the Eaton's department store.{{sfn|Zweig|2012|p=280}}\n{{Stanley Cup champion\n|defence=*[[Jack Marshall (ice hockey)|Jack Marshall]] (Point-Playing-Manager) \n*Connie [[Con Corbeau]] (Point)\n*[[Harry Cameron]] (Cover point)\n*[[George McNamara]](Cover point)\n* [[Eddie Carpenter]] (substitute)\u2020\n|goaltenders=* Harry [[Hap Holmes]]\n*[[Claude Wilson (ice hockey)|Claude Wilson]](sub)\n|wingers=*Allan [[Scotty Davidson]] (Captain)\n*[[James Harriston]]\u2020\n*[[Roy McGiffin]]\u2021 \n*[[Jack Walker (ice hockey)|Jack Walker]]\n*Carol [[Cully Wilson]]\n|centers=*[[Frank Foyston]]\n|player-notes=\u2020 missing from team picture<br>\u2021 also played rover in the Stanley Cup Final\n|non-players=\n*[[Percy Quinn]] (President)\u2020\n*[[Dick Carroll]] (Trainer)\n*[[Frank Carroll (ice hockey)|Frank Carroll]] (Ass't Trainer)\n|engraving-notes=\"1914 Toronto H.C.\" is engraved on the 1947 ring connecting the upper trophy to the barrel\n}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[1913\u201314 NHA season]]\n\n==References==\n* {{cite book |title=A Great Game: The Forgotten Leafs and the Rise of Professional Hockey |last=Harper |first=Stephen J. |year=2013 |publisher=Simon & Schuster Canada |isbn=978-1-4767-1653-4 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Zweig |first1=Eric |year=2012 |title=Stanley Cup: 120 years of hockey supremacy |publisher=Firefly Books |isbn=978-1-77085-104-7 |ref=harv}}\n;Notes\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Toronto Blueshirts}}\n{{Toronto Blueshirts seasons}}\n{{1913\u201314 NHA season by team}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:1913-14 Toronto Hockey Club season}}\n[[Category:Toronto Blueshirts seasons]]\n[[Category:1913\u201314 in Canadian ice hockey by team|Toronto Hockey Club season, 1913-14]]\n[[Category:Stanley Cup championship seasons]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox IcehockeyTeamSeason\n  |Season=1913\u201314\n  |year=1913\n  |Team=Toronto Hockey Club\n  |League=NHA\n  |Conference=\n  |ConferenceRank=\n  |Division=\n  |DivisionRank=\n  |Record=13\u20137\u20130\n  |HomeRecord=8\u20132\u20130\n  |RoadRecord=5\u20135\u20130\n  |GoalsFor=93\n  |GoalsAgainst=65\n  |GeneralManager=[[Percy Quinn]]\n  |Coach=[[Jack Marshall (ice hockey)|Jack Marshall]]\n  |Captain=[[Scotty Davidson]]\n  |AltCaptain=\n  |Arena=[[Mutual Street Arena|Arena Gardens]]\n  |Attendance=\n  |GoalsLeader=\n  |AssistsLeader=\n  |PointsLeader=\n  |PlusMinusLeader=\n  |PIMLeader=\n  |WinsLeader=\n  |GAALeader=\n  |StanleyCup=Yes\n}}\n\nThe '''[[1913\u201314 NHA season|1913\u201314]] [[Toronto Blueshirts|Toronto Hockey Club]] season''' was the second season of the Toronto franchise in the [[National Hockey Association]] (NHA). The Blue Shirts would win the NHA championship in a playoff to take over the [[Stanley Cup]]. The club then played and defeated the [[Victoria Aristocrats]] in the first hockey \"World Series\" against the champion of the [[Pacific Coast Hockey Association]] (PCHA).\n\n==Off-season==\nBruce Ridpath resigned as general manager of the club prior to the season, replaced by Jack Marshall. Ridpath himself tried out as a player but gave up his comeback before the season started. Of the previous season's squad, [[Archie McLean (ice hockey)|Archie McLean]] was dropped and [[Frank Nighbor]] moved to British Columbia. [[Jack Walker (ice hockey)|Jack Walker]], who had played one game with Toronto in the previous season before playing in the Maritime league was added. [[Con Corbeau]] was acquired from the [[Toronto Ontarios]] just before the start of the season.{{sfn|Harper|2013|pp=248\u2013249}}\n\n==Regular season==\n[[File:Torontos.jpg|thumb|right|250px|The 1913\u201314 Torontos]]\nHarry Cameron suffered a separated shoulder and the Torontos acquired [[George McNamara]] from the Ontarios for cash in mid-season. The Torontos had a two-game lead in the standings with two games to go, but lost both to drop into a tie with the Montreal Canadiens. It was rumoured that the Torontos had thrown the last two games to get an extra home game from a final with Montreal.{{sfn|Harper|2013|pp=251\u2013252}}\n\n===Final standings===\n{{1913\u201314 NHA standings |team=BLU}}\n\n===Schedule and results===\n{|class=\"wikitable\" width=\"70%\"\n|- align=\"center\"  bgcolor=\"#dddddd\"\n| '''#''' || '''Date''' || '''Visitor''' || '''Score''' || '''Home''' || '''Record''' || '''Pts'''\n|- align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#bbffbb\"\n| 1 || December 27 || [[Montreal Canadiens]] || 0\u20133 || Toronto || 1\u20130\u20130 || 2\n|- align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#ffbbbb\"\n| 2 || December 30 || Toronto || 3\u20137 || [[Montreal Wanderers]] || 1\u20131\u20130 || 2\n|- align=\"center\" bg